WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.922 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.922 --> 00:00:04.383 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.383 --> 00:00:06.818 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.818 --> 00:00:12.458 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.458 --> 00:00:13.500 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: All right.

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:16.200 align:middle line:90%
Well, we have two more classes.

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:20.270 align:middle line:84%
And this is day two
of trying to grapple

00:00:20.270 --> 00:00:23.370 align:middle line:84%
with the recent big breakthrough
in projection theory.

00:00:23.370 --> 00:00:27.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is sharp projection
theorems part two.

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:31.100 align:middle line:84%
In part two, we're going to
talk about the AD regular case.

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:33.110 align:middle line:84%
So let's first remember
our goal and remember

00:00:33.110 --> 00:00:34.660 align:middle line:90%
what is the AD regular case.

00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:37.400 align:middle line:90%


00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:38.861 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:38.861 --> 00:00:42.290 align:middle line:84%
So our goal is the
Furstenberg set conjecture,

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:46.250 align:middle line:84%
which is a theorem of Orponen,
Shmerkin, Ren, and Wang.

00:00:46.250 --> 00:00:58.880 align:middle line:84%
Says if E contained in R2
is a delta TC set, and then

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:01.580 align:middle line:84%
for every point in
E, there are a bunch

00:01:01.580 --> 00:01:03.830 align:middle line:90%
of delta tubes going through it.

00:01:03.830 --> 00:01:11.060 align:middle line:84%
So T sub x is a
set of delta tubes

00:01:11.060 --> 00:01:17.190 align:middle line:84%
through x and the
directions, if you like,

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:22.540 align:middle line:84%
of this set of delta
tubes is a delta SC set.

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:26.300 align:middle line:90%


00:01:26.300 --> 00:01:27.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:30.420 align:middle line:84%
And parenthetically, we can
assume a couple of things.

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:36.350 align:middle line:84%
We can assume that
this is uniform,

00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:41.390 align:middle line:84%
and also that the number of them
is like delta to the minus S.

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:44.210 align:middle line:90%
And S should be bigger than 0.

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:44.730 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:46.272 align:middle line:84%
So we put all of
these tubes together

00:01:46.272 --> 00:01:47.785 align:middle line:90%
to get one big set of tubes.

00:01:47.785 --> 00:01:50.990 align:middle line:90%


00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:55.490 align:middle line:84%
And the question is, how
many tubes are there?

00:01:55.490 --> 00:02:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So then the conclusion is
that the number of tubes

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.340 align:middle line:84%
is at least a
little fudge factor.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.960 align:middle line:90%


00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:10.190 align:middle line:84%
So this whole thing, I'll
abbreviate like that.

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:12.340 align:middle line:84%
And then the minimum
of a few options.

00:02:12.340 --> 00:02:23.690 align:middle line:90%


00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:27.590 align:middle line:84%
Which we'll call option
A, option B, and option

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:32.640 align:middle line:84%
C. And these exponents
are hard to remember,

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:34.580 align:middle line:84%
but I would prefer to
remember-- for everyone

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:37.580 align:middle line:84%
to think of them in terms of
three different scenarios.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:41.270 align:middle line:84%
So option A, that
corresponds to the--

00:02:41.270 --> 00:02:43.140 align:middle line:90%
I call it the stars scenario.

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:45.050 align:middle line:84%
Have a bunch of points,
and through each, you

00:02:45.050 --> 00:02:46.490 align:middle line:84%
have a bunch of
tubes, and they're

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:50.000 align:middle line:90%
just unrelated to each other.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.470 align:middle line:90%
Option B is more intricate.

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:54.593 align:middle line:90%
It's the integer grid scenario.

00:02:54.593 --> 00:02:57.560 align:middle line:90%


00:02:57.560 --> 00:03:00.960 align:middle line:84%
And option C is a kind
of random scenario.

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:05.680 align:middle line:84%
So E is arbitrary
and T is random.

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:13.490 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:16.238 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:16.238 --> 00:03:18.290 align:middle line:84%
Now it's really a
good idea to think

00:03:18.290 --> 00:03:21.870 align:middle line:84%
about this theorem in these
three different scenarios.

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:23.870 align:middle line:84%
So it's good to separate
out the case where

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:26.810 align:middle line:84%
each one of those
things is the minimum.

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:29.630 align:middle line:84%
So let me do that and
recall for you how much we

00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:31.660 align:middle line:90%
know about each case so far.

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:41.073 align:middle line:90%


00:03:41.073 --> 00:03:43.490 align:middle line:84%
And I said something about
this last time, but what I said

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:45.920 align:middle line:84%
wasn't the best
thing to say, so I

00:03:45.920 --> 00:03:48.590 align:middle line:84%
wanted to do it again
and get it right.

00:03:48.590 --> 00:03:49.320 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:55.150 align:middle line:84%
So there's the case where
A is the minimum option.

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:57.190 align:middle line:84%
And if you do a
little algebra, that

00:03:57.190 --> 00:04:05.200 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to S being at least
as big as T. And in this case--

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:11.080 align:middle line:84%
so if S is at least as big as
T, then the theorem is true.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:12.795 align:middle line:90%
So Furstenberg is true.

00:04:12.795 --> 00:04:17.050 align:middle line:90%


00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:19.124 align:middle line:84%
And it follows just
by double counting.

00:04:19.124 --> 00:04:22.990 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.990 --> 00:04:27.400 align:middle line:84%
So we did it very early in the
course, like on the second day.

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:28.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:31.640 align:middle line:84%
Then I'll come back to B,
which is the most interesting.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:33.470 align:middle line:90%
C is the minimal.

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:39.490 align:middle line:84%
If you do a little algebra,
it's if S plus T is at least 2.

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:44.180 align:middle line:84%
And in this whole range,
where S plus T is at least 2,

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.910 align:middle line:90%
the theorem is also true.

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:49.330 align:middle line:84%
And it's true by
the Fourier method.

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:52.750 align:middle line:84%
So it follows from
the theorem we

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.550 align:middle line:84%
proved in the second or third
week using Fourier analysis.

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.825 align:middle line:84%
So the whole case
where C is minimal,

00:04:58.825 --> 00:05:01.685 align:middle line:90%
we also already understand that.

00:05:01.685 --> 00:05:02.185 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:02.185 --> 00:05:05.650 align:middle line:84%
And that leaves a case
where B is minimal.

00:05:05.650 --> 00:05:09.220 align:middle line:84%
And that's like otherwise,
if neither of these things

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:12.100 align:middle line:90%
are true, then B is minimal.

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
content of this theorem.

00:05:14.990 --> 00:05:24.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is the hard new
thing in the OSW thing.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:27.215 align:middle line:90%


00:05:27.215 --> 00:05:27.715 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:27.715 --> 00:05:30.310 align:middle line:90%


00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:32.710 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:05:32.710 --> 00:05:36.340 align:middle line:84%
Another little comment is
that the number of tubes

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:39.850 align:middle line:84%
is not my favorite
parameter to keep track of.

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:42.310 align:middle line:84%
My favorite parameter
to keep track of

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:49.210 align:middle line:90%
is I'll call it R of ET.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:54.880 align:middle line:84%
Which, in words, is
like the typical number

00:05:54.880 --> 00:06:14.290 align:middle line:84%
of delta balls of E on a typical
tube of T. Let's make a picture.

00:06:14.290 --> 00:06:17.860 align:middle line:84%
So we have some delta
balls, and then we

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:21.310 align:middle line:84%
have some delta tubes
going through them.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:24.460 align:middle line:84%
And in an interesting
scenario, each tube

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:26.060 align:middle line:90%
will have many balls in it.

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:32.068 align:middle line:84%
And R is this number
of balls in a tube.

00:06:32.068 --> 00:06:36.700 align:middle line:84%
So algebraically,
by double counting,

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:38.620 align:middle line:84%
the number of balls
in a tube would

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:42.700 align:middle line:84%
be the number of points
times the number of tubes

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:47.890 align:middle line:84%
going through a point divided
by the number of tubes.

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:50.390 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the
algebraic definition of R.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:55.330 align:middle line:84%
And then it's easy to convert
bounds for T into bounds for R.

00:06:55.330 --> 00:07:04.630 align:middle line:84%
So our theorem is equivalent
to that R is upper bounded

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:08.440 align:middle line:90%
by the maximum of three things.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:11.110 align:middle line:90%
Scenario one is A.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:14.350 align:middle line:84%
So scenario one, the
number of balls per tube

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:18.640 align:middle line:84%
is one, which is
always easy to arrange.

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:21.320 align:middle line:84%
B, you have to do a
little computation.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:23.513 align:middle line:90%
It works out to this.

00:07:23.513 --> 00:07:25.930 align:middle line:84%
I don't really care what the
exponent-- it's not important

00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:26.990 align:middle line:90%
what the exponents are.

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:33.900 align:middle line:84%
And C is delta to the
negative T plus 1.

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:34.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:36.520 align:middle line:84%
And this delta to
the negative T plus 1

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:39.580 align:middle line:84%
has a nice interpretation which
might clarify a little bit what

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:41.720 align:middle line:90%
we mean by this random case.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:45.460 align:middle line:90%
So if E is a set--

00:07:45.460 --> 00:07:52.942 align:middle line:84%
is a delta TC set, so the size
of E is delta to the minus T.

00:07:52.942 --> 00:07:53.900 align:middle line:90%
Let me say it this way.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:58.540 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that E is a set
of delta to the minus T

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:03.040 align:middle line:90%
delta balls in the unit ball.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:08.470 align:middle line:84%
And then I take the average
over any choice of delta

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:14.050 align:middle line:84%
by 1 rectangles of the
number of delta balls

00:08:14.050 --> 00:08:16.060 align:middle line:90%
that the rectangle covers.

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:21.430 align:middle line:84%
You would get delta
to the minus T plus 1.

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:26.570 align:middle line:84%
So it's not difficult to locate
rectangles with that richness.

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:29.170 align:middle line:84%
Almost any rectangle
would do the job.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:32.260 align:middle line:84%
And scenario C is when
the rectangles just

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:33.520 align:middle line:90%
have this average richness.

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:35.270 align:middle line:84%
There's really nothing
special about them.

00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:44.620 align:middle line:90%


00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:45.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:48.160 align:middle line:84%
So next, let's remember--
so our goal today

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:50.390 align:middle line:84%
is to talk about
the AD regular case.

00:08:50.390 --> 00:08:53.220 align:middle line:84%
So let's remember what
is the AD regular case.

00:08:53.220 --> 00:09:07.400 align:middle line:90%


00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:07.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:14.200 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to suppose
that E is uniform.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:19.510 align:middle line:84%
So that means that our delta
is some capital delta to the M,

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:20.835 align:middle line:90%
where M is a large number.

00:09:20.835 --> 00:09:23.500 align:middle line:90%


00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:26.110 align:middle line:84%
And the uniformity
is that if I take E

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:30.530 align:middle line:84%
and I intersect it with a cube
of side length delta to the j,

00:09:30.530 --> 00:09:35.500 align:middle line:84%
and I ask about its delta to
the j plus 1 covering number,

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:47.820 align:middle line:84%
that's around some beta j
for all the dyadic Q delta j

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:49.060 align:middle line:90%
that intersect.

00:09:49.060 --> 00:09:54.600 align:middle line:90%


00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:55.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:55.120 --> 00:09:57.520 align:middle line:84%
So these beta j are
the branching numbers.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:01.380 align:middle line:84%
We drew pictures last time
to illustrate what they mean.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:09.760 align:middle line:84%
And so definition would be that
E is C alpha is to be regular.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:17.910 align:middle line:84%
So actually let's say it's
a delta TC AD regular set

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:22.060 align:middle line:84%
if has this branching
structure like above

00:10:22.060 --> 00:10:29.410 align:middle line:84%
and if I take the product j
equals 1 to capital J of beta j.

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:33.240 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the
delta j covering number--

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:35.450 align:middle line:84%
delta to the j covering
number of our set.

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:38.220 align:middle line:90%


00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:44.040 align:middle line:84%
It is at most C times delta
to the j to the minus t,

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:47.100 align:middle line:84%
and it is at least
1 over C times

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:49.450 align:middle line:90%
delta to the j to the minus t.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:54.580 align:middle line:90%


00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:55.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:55.080 --> 00:11:06.000 align:middle line:90%


00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:06.665 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:11:06.665 --> 00:11:11.970 align:middle line:90%


00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:15.810 align:middle line:84%
So let's label all these
hypotheses in our theorem

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:17.966 align:middle line:90%
by H, our hypotheses.

00:11:17.966 --> 00:11:21.480 align:middle line:90%


00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:24.840 align:middle line:84%
And what we'd like to understand
is given these hypotheses,

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:28.110 align:middle line:90%
how big could R be?

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:32.080 align:middle line:84%
And for today, we're going to
talk about the AD regular case.

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:33.520 align:middle line:90%
So let's give that a name.

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:44.400 align:middle line:84%
So RAD of ST delta C. That
is the maximum over E and T

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:52.410 align:middle line:84%
obey our hypotheses,
and E is a delta TC AD

00:11:52.410 --> 00:12:02.060 align:middle line:84%
regular of r of E and T. How
big could it be in this case?

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:02.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:04.600 align:middle line:84%
It's really a mouthful
of parameters,

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:08.640 align:middle line:84%
so let me just say, to reduce
a little bit for today,

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:11.160 align:middle line:90%
we'll have C equals 1.

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:13.870 align:middle line:84%
So that means it's
really AD regular,

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:18.360 align:middle line:84%
and everything we say
actually will work for small c

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:25.050 align:middle line:84%
that are bigger than E. That
will allow us to not write

00:12:25.050 --> 00:12:28.305 align:middle line:84%
the letter C. And
then S and T will not

00:12:28.305 --> 00:12:29.680 align:middle line:84%
be changing through
our argument,

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:31.290 align:middle line:84%
so I won't write
them every time.

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:37.865 align:middle line:84%
So now I'll just abbreviate
it as RAD of delta.

00:12:37.865 --> 00:12:40.735 align:middle line:90%


00:12:40.735 --> 00:12:41.235 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:41.235 --> 00:12:46.230 align:middle line:90%


00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:47.430 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:53.640 align:middle line:84%
So the theorem that
Orponen and Shmerkin proved

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:57.210 align:middle line:84%
is that they proved this
thing in the AD case.

00:12:57.210 --> 00:13:04.900 align:middle line:84%
So RAD ST delta is
indeed bounded by that.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:15.812 align:middle line:90%


00:13:15.812 --> 00:13:19.590 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure I copied it right.

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:20.750 align:middle line:90%
Got the minus signs wrong.

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:32.280 align:middle line:90%


00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:34.650 align:middle line:84%
So that's our goal for
today is to understand

00:13:34.650 --> 00:13:37.440 align:middle line:84%
this theorem, which is a
really important special case

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:38.165 align:middle line:90%
of that theorem.

00:13:38.165 --> 00:13:43.260 align:middle line:90%


00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:45.360 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:49.230 align:middle line:84%
So it's clearly a special
case of that theorem.

00:13:49.230 --> 00:13:51.870 align:middle line:84%
And at first it might seem
like a very special case,

00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:54.120 align:middle line:84%
because these branching
function basically-- there's

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:56.410 align:middle line:84%
a huge range of what the
branching function could be,

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:58.830 align:middle line:84%
and AD regular is just
one particular choice

00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:00.100 align:middle line:90%
in this huge range.

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.020 align:middle line:84%
But it's a particularly
important case,

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:05.670 align:middle line:84%
and we'll see tomorrow or
next class that this is really

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:07.230 align:middle line:90%
a crucial case.

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:09.240 align:middle line:84%
It plays a big role in
understanding the theorem

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:11.695 align:middle line:90%
in general.

00:14:11.695 --> 00:14:12.195 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:12.195 --> 00:14:16.200 align:middle line:90%


00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:18.480 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:19.965 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:14:19.965 --> 00:14:22.350 align:middle line:84%
It was a really
important realization

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.600 align:middle line:84%
in thinking about this theorem
that we should break it

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:25.630 align:middle line:90%
into cases.

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:28.560 align:middle line:84%
The different cases have their
different things that are useful

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:32.130 align:middle line:84%
and their different
things that are difficult.

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:34.780 align:middle line:90%
And so that recognition is key.

00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:36.690 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing I want
to try to talk about

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:40.320 align:middle line:84%
is what is special
about AD regular sets

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:44.340 align:middle line:84%
that we could use to get a
handle on them that we couldn't

00:14:44.340 --> 00:14:48.030 align:middle line:90%
use just for the general setup.

00:14:48.030 --> 00:14:48.700 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:15:03.780 align:middle line:90%


00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:06.550 align:middle line:84%
So this proof is
quite difficult.

00:15:06.550 --> 00:15:07.810 align:middle line:90%
We won't do all of it.

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:11.490 align:middle line:84%
But I would like to share
some key ideas about it, which

00:15:11.490 --> 00:15:16.380 align:middle line:84%
I think are really cool and
are worth taking with you away

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:18.960 align:middle line:90%
from this class.

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:19.460 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:41.540 align:middle line:90%


00:15:41.540 --> 00:15:42.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:46.070 align:middle line:84%
So in a nutshell, the
important special thing

00:15:46.070 --> 00:15:49.220 align:middle line:84%
about AD regular
sets is in this lemma

00:15:49.220 --> 00:15:52.790 align:middle line:84%
that has a one board
proof, which is called

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:55.150 align:middle line:90%
the submultiplicative lemma.

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:58.250 align:middle line:90%


00:15:58.250 --> 00:15:59.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:04.410 align:middle line:90%
So it says that RAD of delta--

00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:06.020 align:middle line:90%
let me put it this way.

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:09.120 align:middle line:84%
If delta is delta
1 times delta 2,

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:13.100 align:middle line:84%
then RAD of delta
is bounded by--

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:14.760 align:middle line:90%
and with a little bit of fudge--

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:19.710 align:middle line:84%
RAD of delta 1
times RAD delta 2.

00:16:19.710 --> 00:16:24.380 align:middle line:90%


00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:27.710 align:middle line:90%
That is submultiplicative.

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:33.050 align:middle line:84%
And it follows from
understanding, thinking

00:16:33.050 --> 00:16:38.210 align:middle line:84%
a lot about a picture
of an AD regular set.

00:16:38.210 --> 00:16:38.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So remember that E is
a set of delta balls

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:49.490 align:middle line:84%
and T is the set of delta
tubes, and we're going

00:16:49.490 --> 00:16:52.970 align:middle line:90%
to imagine thickening them.

00:16:52.970 --> 00:16:56.450 align:middle line:84%
So in this setup
here, delta is smaller

00:16:56.450 --> 00:17:00.020 align:middle line:84%
than delta 1 and delta 2,
which are smaller than 1.

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:02.640 align:middle line:84%
So delta 1 and delta 2 are
each bigger than delta.

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:07.339 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to thicken
them and I'll get E1,

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:11.810 align:middle line:84%
I'll call it, which are
the delta 1 balls around E,

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:14.874 align:middle line:90%
and T1, which are delta 1 tubes.

00:17:14.874 --> 00:17:18.890 align:middle line:90%


00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:19.560 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:21.150 align:middle line:90%
So what does it look like?

00:17:21.150 --> 00:17:32.100 align:middle line:84%
Let's think about E and
thickening E. So here is E1.

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:33.810 align:middle line:90%
It is a bunch of circles.

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:37.655 align:middle line:90%
Each circle has radius delta 1.

00:17:37.655 --> 00:17:41.140 align:middle line:84%
And inside of those circles,
there are some delta balls.

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:50.600 align:middle line:90%


00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:59.630 align:middle line:84%
And those guys are
my delta balls E. OK.

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:05.960 align:middle line:90%
Now, T1 are some delta 1 tubes.

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:08.605 align:middle line:90%
So they might look like this.

00:18:08.605 --> 00:18:11.300 align:middle line:90%


00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:12.820 align:middle line:90%
Let's put one more ball up here.

00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:24.890 align:middle line:90%


00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:26.160 align:middle line:90%
That looks like that.

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:28.915 align:middle line:90%
So those are my fat tubes, T1.

00:18:28.915 --> 00:18:31.850 align:middle line:90%


00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:37.520 align:middle line:84%
And then inside of them,
there are some delta tubes T2.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:42.095 align:middle line:90%
So let me draw that.

00:18:42.095 --> 00:18:44.310 align:middle line:84%
I've got too many, but
I'll try to give some idea.

00:18:44.310 --> 00:18:49.550 align:middle line:84%
So through this
point here, there

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:52.310 align:middle line:84%
might be a couple
of red tubes that

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:55.460 align:middle line:90%
are inside of that orange tube.

00:18:55.460 --> 00:19:00.200 align:middle line:84%
And then there might be
a couple of red tubes

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:02.710 align:middle line:84%
that are inside of
that orange tube.

00:19:02.710 --> 00:19:05.250 align:middle line:90%


00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:05.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:05.750 --> 00:19:08.100 align:middle line:84%
I just drew the ones
through this point.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.470 align:middle line:84%
Experience has taught
me that if I draw more,

00:19:10.470 --> 00:19:12.150 align:middle line:90%
this picture will get too messy.

00:19:12.150 --> 00:19:16.080 align:middle line:84%
But you should imagine that this
is happening at every point.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:16.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:21.410 align:middle line:90%


00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:23.750 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:25.163 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:25.163 --> 00:19:34.490 align:middle line:84%
So the first observation
is that E1 and T1 obey

00:19:34.490 --> 00:19:37.120 align:middle line:90%
the hypotheses of our theorem.

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:41.210 align:middle line:90%


00:19:41.210 --> 00:19:45.230 align:middle line:84%
Because actually, if you
take a delta T set of balls

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:47.400 align:middle line:84%
and you thicken them
up to radius delta 1,

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:50.840 align:middle line:84%
you get a delta
1 T set of balls.

00:19:50.840 --> 00:19:53.640 align:middle line:84%
At least, because
if it's uniform.

00:19:53.640 --> 00:19:57.590 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at who's
going through this point,

00:19:57.590 --> 00:20:02.910 align:middle line:84%
we have a delta S set of
directions leaving that point.

00:20:02.910 --> 00:20:05.160 align:middle line:84%
And if you thicken
them up a little bit,

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:07.820 align:middle line:84%
you get the directions
corresponding

00:20:07.820 --> 00:20:09.120 align:middle line:90%
to the orange tubes.

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:14.360 align:middle line:84%
And that will be a delta
1 S set of directions.

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:16.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:16.340 --> 00:20:16.840 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:21.910 align:middle line:90%


00:20:21.910 --> 00:20:22.430 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:24.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:24.010 --> 00:20:26.020 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me
put the punch line,

00:20:26.020 --> 00:20:28.600 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll think
through why this works.

00:20:28.600 --> 00:20:32.000 align:middle line:90%
So RAD of delta.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.410 align:middle line:84%
That's the number of
white balls in a red tube.

00:20:35.410 --> 00:20:41.140 align:middle line:84%
But that's bounded by the
number of delta 1 balls

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:42.930 align:middle line:90%
in a delta 1 tube.

00:20:42.930 --> 00:20:47.080 align:middle line:90%


00:20:47.080 --> 00:20:49.750 align:middle line:84%
So I look in this orange tube,
I see how many of these balls

00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:59.560 align:middle line:84%
there are, times the number
of delta balls in a delta tube

00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:03.890 align:middle line:90%
within 1 delta 1 bar.

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:09.010 align:middle line:90%


00:21:09.010 --> 00:21:12.200 align:middle line:84%
So if I'm looking at
this red tube here,

00:21:12.200 --> 00:21:14.890 align:middle line:84%
I want to know how many
delta balls are in it.

00:21:14.890 --> 00:21:18.670 align:middle line:84%
It's bounded by the
number of big balls

00:21:18.670 --> 00:21:23.260 align:middle line:84%
that it enters times the
number of little balls

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:24.630 align:middle line:90%
in each of the big balls.

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:29.920 align:middle line:90%


00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:30.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:36.310 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to relate these
two things to our problem

00:21:36.310 --> 00:21:38.830 align:middle line:90%
at a coarser scale.

00:21:38.830 --> 00:21:44.840 align:middle line:84%
And this one here, well, E1
and T1 obey our hypotheses.

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:49.710 align:middle line:84%
So this one here is
bounded by RAD delta 1.

00:21:49.710 --> 00:21:52.750 align:middle line:90%


00:21:52.750 --> 00:22:01.210 align:middle line:84%
Now here, if you take E
and T and you restrict them

00:22:01.210 --> 00:22:07.180 align:middle line:84%
to a delta 1 ball,
and then you magnify

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:13.930 align:middle line:84%
it to bring it up to scale one,
this also obeys our hypotheses.

00:22:13.930 --> 00:22:19.520 align:middle line:84%
So if you look inside of here,
you see a little delta TS set.

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:22.966 align:middle line:90%


00:22:22.966 --> 00:22:28.390 align:middle line:84%
This and these red tubes, that's
the same situation on a smaller

00:22:28.390 --> 00:22:30.920 align:middle line:90%
scale or on a coarser scale.

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:37.430 align:middle line:84%
So when you blow this
up, if you blow it up,

00:22:37.430 --> 00:22:45.760 align:middle line:84%
then you get delta 2 balls and
delta 2 tubes in the unit ball.

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:52.245 align:middle line:84%
So this guy is bounded
by the RAD of delta 2.

00:22:52.245 --> 00:23:02.530 align:middle line:90%


00:23:02.530 --> 00:23:03.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:03.130 --> 00:23:05.760 align:middle line:84%
Let me call this claim
one and claim two.

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:10.270 align:middle line:90%


00:23:10.270 --> 00:23:12.520 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:16.300 align:middle line:84%
So this picture is perhaps
the most important thing

00:23:16.300 --> 00:23:19.660 align:middle line:84%
to take away from this
proof in this class.

00:23:19.660 --> 00:23:23.115 align:middle line:84%
So take a moment and see if you
have questions about this proof.

00:23:23.115 --> 00:23:29.820 align:middle line:90%


00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:41.447 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:41.447 --> 00:23:42.280 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:23:42.280 --> 00:23:42.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:42.860 --> 00:23:45.610 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
do we need to check

00:23:45.610 --> 00:23:47.330 align:middle line:90%
that everything is AD regular.

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:47.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:47.830 --> 00:23:48.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:48.330 --> 00:23:51.220 align:middle line:84%
So let me add to these claims,
and then if we want to,

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:54.400 align:middle line:84%
we can add details to the
proof of these claims.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:58.660 align:middle line:84%
E1 and T1 obey the hypotheses,
and they're AD regular.

00:23:58.660 --> 00:24:01.880 align:middle line:84%
And we need that this blow
up here obeys the hypotheses

00:24:01.880 --> 00:24:03.080 align:middle line:90%
and it's AD regular.

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:04.580 align:middle line:84%
And if you believe
those two things,

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:06.830 align:middle line:84%
then you can plug-- you just
plug in and you get that.

00:24:06.830 --> 00:24:10.640 align:middle line:90%


00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:11.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:24:11.140 --> 00:24:13.473 align:middle line:84%
And we can talk a little bit
more about those two things

00:24:13.473 --> 00:24:15.187 align:middle line:90%
if you want.

00:24:15.187 --> 00:24:16.770 align:middle line:84%
Are there other
questions or comments?

00:24:16.770 --> 00:24:27.010 align:middle line:90%


00:24:27.010 --> 00:24:27.512 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:27.512 --> 00:24:28.970 align:middle line:84%
So I'll probably
add a little more,

00:24:28.970 --> 00:24:31.870 align:middle line:84%
but actually, I wanted to
ask you all a question.

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:35.830 align:middle line:84%
In this argument, where did
we take advantage of the fact

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:38.190 align:middle line:84%
that the original
E was AD regular?

00:24:38.190 --> 00:24:45.970 align:middle line:90%


00:24:45.970 --> 00:24:47.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, Jonathan?

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:52.997 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is it like picking one
delta 1 ball and magnifying it?

00:24:52.997 --> 00:24:53.830 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:24:53.830 --> 00:24:57.400 align:middle line:84%
So it's related to when we
picked this one delta 1 ball

00:24:57.400 --> 00:24:58.940 align:middle line:90%
and magnified it.

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:00.980 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:01.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.430 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about one and
two a little more carefully.

00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:11.650 align:middle line:90%


00:25:11.650 --> 00:25:12.255 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:25:12.255 --> 00:25:23.140 align:middle line:90%


00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:29.200 align:middle line:90%
So let's discuss one and two.

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:31.090 align:middle line:90%
OK, so point one.

00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:35.120 align:middle line:90%
If E and T are uniform--

00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:37.210 align:middle line:84%
which we can pretty much
assume from the-- which

00:25:37.210 --> 00:25:41.020 align:middle line:84%
we can assume from the
beginning with a little pruning.

00:25:41.020 --> 00:26:01.480 align:middle line:84%
Then E delta T implies that
E1 is delta 1T and Tx delta S

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:06.850 align:middle line:90%
implies that T1x is delta 1x.

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:11.340 align:middle line:90%


00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:16.120 align:middle line:84%
And also, if E is
AD regular, that

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:19.810 align:middle line:90%
implies that E1 is AD regular.

00:26:19.810 --> 00:26:22.630 align:middle line:84%
Because this is saying all
the branching numbers of E

00:26:22.630 --> 00:26:24.380 align:middle line:90%
are the same as each other.

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:26.710 align:middle line:84%
And this is saying that all
the branching numbers of E

00:26:26.710 --> 00:26:29.690 align:middle line:84%
down to the depth of delta 1
are the same as each other.

00:26:29.690 --> 00:26:32.890 align:middle line:90%


00:26:32.890 --> 00:26:34.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:41.050 align:middle line:84%
We didn't need E to be a
regular to do this or this,

00:26:41.050 --> 00:26:44.620 align:middle line:90%
but it comes in in part two.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:53.260 align:middle line:84%
So because E is AD
regular, then we

00:26:53.260 --> 00:26:58.240 align:middle line:84%
get that if you take E and you
intersect it with a small ball

00:26:58.240 --> 00:27:05.590 align:middle line:84%
and magnify it, then
this is a delta--

00:27:05.590 --> 00:27:08.535 align:middle line:90%
I guess delta 2T and AD regular.

00:27:08.535 --> 00:27:12.690 align:middle line:90%


00:27:12.690 --> 00:27:17.110 align:middle line:84%
So let me illustrate this with
pictures instead of equations.

00:27:17.110 --> 00:27:18.610 align:middle line:90%
So what does it look like?

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:21.760 align:middle line:84%
Let's draw an AD regular set
and a not AD regular set,

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:23.520 align:middle line:90%
and we'll look at both of them.

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:28.895 align:middle line:84%
So if E is AD
regular, what do I do?

00:27:28.895 --> 00:27:34.140 align:middle line:90%


00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:35.735 align:middle line:90%
I pick, say, four of them.

00:27:35.735 --> 00:27:42.608 align:middle line:90%


00:27:42.608 --> 00:27:43.775 align:middle line:90%
Let me do this in the color.

00:27:43.775 --> 00:27:52.710 align:middle line:90%


00:27:52.710 --> 00:27:55.565 align:middle line:84%
Then for each one that I
picked, I subdivide it.

00:27:55.565 --> 00:28:02.250 align:middle line:90%


00:28:02.250 --> 00:28:04.085 align:middle line:90%
And I pick four of them.

00:28:04.085 --> 00:28:09.440 align:middle line:90%


00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:09.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:10.690 align:middle line:90%
I'll stop drawing.

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:12.090 align:middle line:90%
You get the idea.

00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:12.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:14.800 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is a
self-similar construction.

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:18.040 align:middle line:84%
If I take this thing in
here and I blow it up,

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:19.690 align:middle line:84%
it's just like what
I started with.

00:28:19.690 --> 00:28:22.770 align:middle line:84%
So it will be AD regular and
it will be-- in particular,

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:28.680 align:middle line:84%
in delta, there will be a delta
T set for the appropriate delta.

00:28:28.680 --> 00:28:29.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:35.190 align:middle line:84%
What would it look like
if E was not AD regular?

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:42.010 align:middle line:84%
Well, for example, I might
do the following thing.

00:28:42.010 --> 00:28:44.680 align:middle line:84%
I might cut it into
a four by four grid,

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:47.290 align:middle line:84%
and I might take
all of the boxes.

00:28:47.290 --> 00:28:52.200 align:middle line:84%
And then I could cut each one
of them into a four by four grid

00:28:52.200 --> 00:28:55.350 align:middle line:90%
and pick just one box.

00:28:55.350 --> 00:28:58.870 align:middle line:84%
So this was the well-spaced
example that we drew last time.

00:28:58.870 --> 00:29:03.850 align:middle line:90%


00:29:03.850 --> 00:29:04.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:07.150 align:middle line:84%
So this whole thing
is a delta T set.

00:29:07.150 --> 00:29:10.770 align:middle line:84%
But if I took just one of
these boxes, what I would see

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:12.070 align:middle line:90%
is much more concentrated.

00:29:12.070 --> 00:29:13.860 align:middle line:90%
This is not a delta T set.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:21.720 align:middle line:84%
So if I were to take
this guy and take it out

00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:26.520 align:middle line:84%
here and magnify it, then inside
of here I would just see this.

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:35.820 align:middle line:84%
This here is a blank T set, but
this here is not a blank T set.

00:29:35.820 --> 00:29:39.960 align:middle line:84%
Whereas in the AD regular case,
if I were to take one of these

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:44.400 align:middle line:84%
and bring it out and magnify it,
then what I would see in here

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:47.130 align:middle line:84%
would be very similar
to the original set.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:56.850 align:middle line:84%
This is similar to E. So
this here is a blank T set

00:29:56.850 --> 00:29:58.530 align:middle line:90%
and it's AD regular.

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:01.470 align:middle line:84%
And that thing in there
is still a blank T set

00:30:01.470 --> 00:30:02.900 align:middle line:90%
and it's still AD regular.

00:30:02.900 --> 00:30:06.060 align:middle line:90%


00:30:06.060 --> 00:30:06.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:09.370 align:middle line:84%
So this is the special
feature AD regular.

00:30:09.370 --> 00:30:10.920 align:middle line:84%
The word regular
refers to the fact

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:13.140 align:middle line:84%
that all the different
scales look the same.

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:18.420 align:middle line:84%
And so when we look
inside this ball here,

00:30:18.420 --> 00:30:21.570 align:middle line:84%
we have another example of our
original problem at a coarser

00:30:21.570 --> 00:30:22.740 align:middle line:90%
scale.

00:30:22.740 --> 00:30:26.050 align:middle line:84%
And that feeds into
an inductive argument.

00:30:26.050 --> 00:30:29.640 align:middle line:84%
For example, we can say this
submultiplicative lemma.

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:30.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:32.470 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The first
equality over there,

00:30:32.470 --> 00:30:35.490 align:middle line:84%
do you need some of
uniformity on the number

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:38.120 align:middle line:90%
of the balls from A to C?

00:30:38.120 --> 00:30:40.620 align:middle line:84%
Because RAD is like the average,
and you're saying something

00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:43.200 align:middle line:84%
like the average is less
than or equal to [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:44.460 align:middle line:90%
the averages.

00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:45.300 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:30:45.300 --> 00:30:46.028 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:30:46.028 --> 00:30:46.570 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:50.220 align:middle line:90%


00:30:50.220 --> 00:30:50.940 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:51.940 align:middle line:90%
That is a good point.

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:57.030 align:middle line:84%
So the comment is that RAD was
defined as an average number

00:30:57.030 --> 00:30:58.540 align:middle line:90%
of delta tubes per delta ball.

00:30:58.540 --> 00:31:02.440 align:middle line:84%
And here I was pretending that
all the tubes are average.

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:06.600 align:middle line:84%
So let's call this
a proof sketch.

00:31:06.600 --> 00:31:09.310 align:middle line:90%


00:31:09.310 --> 00:31:11.040 align:middle line:90%
You do need some uniformity.

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:12.790 align:middle line:84%
If you think back to
the original setting,

00:31:12.790 --> 00:31:15.830 align:middle line:84%
you have this set E and then
you draw all these tubes.

00:31:15.830 --> 00:31:19.640 align:middle line:84%
You can sort them by how many
delta tubes are in each one.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:23.500 align:middle line:84%
And you take the category
that has the most delta tubes,

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:25.940 align:middle line:84%
and that will still
you can work with that.

00:31:25.940 --> 00:31:27.192 align:middle line:90%
So you can do--

00:31:27.192 --> 00:31:28.000 align:middle line:90%
you're correct.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:32.800 align:middle line:84%
We have to uniformize it, and
it's possible to uniformize it.

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:33.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:35.330 align:middle line:90%
So let me describe that.

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:49.510 align:middle line:84%
So we can do some
uniformizing so all tubes

00:31:49.510 --> 00:31:51.540 align:middle line:90%
have the same number of balls.

00:31:51.540 --> 00:32:01.110 align:middle line:90%


00:32:01.110 --> 00:32:01.838 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:01.838 --> 00:32:03.005 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:32:03.005 --> 00:32:05.760 align:middle line:90%


00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:06.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:08.460 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:32:08.460 --> 00:32:09.430 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:32:09.430 --> 00:32:13.980 align:middle line:84%
So this little lemma
is very important.

00:32:13.980 --> 00:32:16.560 align:middle line:84%
For people who have
seen some other things

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:19.230 align:middle line:84%
in harmonic analysis, there's
a submultiplicative lemma

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:21.550 align:middle line:84%
that's sort of like this
in decoupling theory.

00:32:21.550 --> 00:32:24.150 align:middle line:84%
And it's the beginning of
what's special about decoupling.

00:32:24.150 --> 00:32:25.900 align:middle line:84%
If those words don't
mean anything to you,

00:32:25.900 --> 00:32:28.170 align:middle line:90%
don't worry about it.

00:32:28.170 --> 00:32:31.710 align:middle line:84%
So let me show you some
corollaries, some applications

00:32:31.710 --> 00:32:34.470 align:middle line:90%
of this lemma.

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:37.560 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll go in
earnest into using

00:32:37.560 --> 00:32:39.900 align:middle line:90%
it to prove this theorem.

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:40.565 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:32:40.565 --> 00:32:57.610 align:middle line:90%


00:32:57.610 --> 00:32:58.110 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:32:58.110 --> 00:33:01.610 align:middle line:84%
So the first application
is sort of tongue in cheek,

00:33:01.610 --> 00:33:06.290 align:middle line:84%
but also I think it's
philosophically important.

00:33:06.290 --> 00:33:07.880 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to call it--

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:09.096 align:middle line:90%
so applications.

00:33:09.096 --> 00:33:12.170 align:middle line:90%


00:33:12.170 --> 00:33:20.720 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to call it a brute
force proof of our theorem,

00:33:20.720 --> 00:33:27.290 align:middle line:84%
of theorem of the
AD regular case.

00:33:27.290 --> 00:33:28.645 align:middle line:90%
So here's how it goes.

00:33:28.645 --> 00:33:31.610 align:middle line:90%


00:33:31.610 --> 00:33:44.900 align:middle line:84%
So for some specific delta
0, we check by brute force

00:33:44.900 --> 00:33:54.085 align:middle line:84%
that RAD ST delta is bounded
by the right-hand side.

00:33:54.085 --> 00:33:56.658 align:middle line:90%


00:33:56.658 --> 00:33:58.200 align:middle line:84%
We won't be able to
get it perfectly,

00:33:58.200 --> 00:33:59.742 align:middle line:84%
but we could get
something like this.

00:33:59.742 --> 00:34:02.680 align:middle line:90%


00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:03.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:03.180 --> 00:34:04.222 align:middle line:90%
So how could you do this?

00:34:04.222 --> 00:34:08.630 align:middle line:84%
Once you fix a particular
delta 0, like 1 over a million,

00:34:08.630 --> 00:34:11.690 align:middle line:84%
there are really only
finitely many different ways

00:34:11.690 --> 00:34:13.366 align:middle line:84%
you could arrange
the delta balls,

00:34:13.366 --> 00:34:15.199 align:middle line:84%
and there are really
only finitely many ways

00:34:15.199 --> 00:34:16.199 align:middle line:90%
you could put the tubes.

00:34:16.199 --> 00:34:18.380 align:middle line:84%
So there's a giant
brute force calculation

00:34:18.380 --> 00:34:20.750 align:middle line:84%
that you couldn't really
do but we could imagine,

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:24.050 align:middle line:90%
and you could just check this.

00:34:24.050 --> 00:34:33.170 align:middle line:84%
Once you have this, then you
use the submultiplicative lemma

00:34:33.170 --> 00:34:34.120 align:middle line:90%
many times.

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:37.219 align:middle line:90%


00:34:37.219 --> 00:34:40.370 align:middle line:84%
And so when you
used it once, you

00:34:40.370 --> 00:34:43.880 align:middle line:84%
would get RAD ST
delta 0 squared.

00:34:43.880 --> 00:34:47.510 align:middle line:84%
That would be bounded by
right-hand side times delta

00:34:47.510 --> 00:34:51.590 align:middle line:90%
squared to the minus epsilon.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:54.750 align:middle line:84%
Because the right-hand side
is just the power of delta 0,

00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:55.590 align:middle line:90%
so it multiplies.

00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:59.155 align:middle line:84%
Everything fits
and you keep going.

00:34:59.155 --> 00:35:04.895 align:middle line:90%


00:35:04.895 --> 00:35:05.395 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:05.395 --> 00:35:08.850 align:middle line:90%


00:35:08.850 --> 00:35:10.970 align:middle line:84%
So this brute force
computation is so large

00:35:10.970 --> 00:35:12.830 align:middle line:84%
that it's out of the
question to do it even

00:35:12.830 --> 00:35:15.590 align:middle line:90%
with a supercomputer, et cetera.

00:35:15.590 --> 00:35:18.710 align:middle line:84%
Nevertheless, it
is worth noticing

00:35:18.710 --> 00:35:23.510 align:middle line:84%
that this very difficult
theorem has a one blackboard

00:35:23.510 --> 00:35:26.990 align:middle line:84%
proof up to a brute
force computation,

00:35:26.990 --> 00:35:28.760 align:middle line:90%
up to a finite computation.

00:35:28.760 --> 00:35:30.510 align:middle line:90%
Most difficult theorems in math.

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:33.217 align:middle line:84%
It's not obvious how to reduce
to a finite computation.

00:35:33.217 --> 00:35:34.800 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't say this
is obvious either,

00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:36.210 align:middle line:84%
but for most difficult
theorems in math,

00:35:36.210 --> 00:35:38.090 align:middle line:84%
there's not a half page
argument to reduce it

00:35:38.090 --> 00:35:39.240 align:middle line:90%
to a finite computation.

00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:40.380 align:middle line:90%
For this one, there is.

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:42.240 align:middle line:84%
So it shows that this
is quite important.

00:35:42.240 --> 00:35:48.750 align:middle line:90%


00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:49.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:49.250 --> 00:35:53.060 align:middle line:90%
Let me give another application.

00:35:53.060 --> 00:35:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Second application
is the general case.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:00.900 align:middle line:84%
General AD versus
the projective AD.

00:36:00.900 --> 00:36:04.580 align:middle line:90%


00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:07.565 align:middle line:84%
So the course was called
projection theory.

00:36:07.565 --> 00:36:09.440 align:middle line:84%
And at the beginning we
talked about problems

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:11.370 align:middle line:90%
about orthogonal projections.

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:13.367 align:middle line:84%
And this theorem is
really more general.

00:36:13.367 --> 00:36:14.700 align:middle line:90%
I guess I've erased the theorem.

00:36:14.700 --> 00:36:16.242 align:middle line:84%
The theorem we're
talking about today

00:36:16.242 --> 00:36:19.730 align:middle line:84%
is more general than just
orthogonal projections.

00:36:19.730 --> 00:36:21.938 align:middle line:84%
And if you had some
orthogonal projections,

00:36:21.938 --> 00:36:23.480 align:middle line:84%
the way you would
get all these tubes

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:25.890 align:middle line:84%
is you would pick a direction
from your direction set,

00:36:25.890 --> 00:36:27.860 align:middle line:84%
and then you would
get a bunch of tubes

00:36:27.860 --> 00:36:30.860 align:middle line:84%
in that direction
that cover your set.

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:34.460 align:middle line:90%
So I make a definition.

00:36:34.460 --> 00:36:46.010 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that ET is
projective if for every x in E,

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:49.342 align:middle line:84%
the direction set
of the tubes Tx--

00:36:49.342 --> 00:36:50.300 align:middle line:90%
let me put it this way.

00:36:50.300 --> 00:36:53.900 align:middle line:84%
For every x1 and x2
in E, the direction

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:56.090 align:middle line:84%
of the tubes through
x1 is the same

00:36:56.090 --> 00:37:01.490 align:middle line:84%
as the direction of
the tubes through x2.

00:37:01.490 --> 00:37:04.050 align:middle line:84%
In other words, you have
just one set of directions,

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:09.260 align:middle line:84%
and Tx is all the tubes through
x in that set of directions.

00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:09.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:09.780 --> 00:37:12.270 align:middle line:84%
So if you think about the
problem that we wrote down,

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:13.530 align:middle line:90%
this is a very special case.

00:37:13.530 --> 00:37:15.620 align:middle line:84%
So it used to be at
every point you picked

00:37:15.620 --> 00:37:18.510 align:middle line:84%
your own independent
set of tubes,

00:37:18.510 --> 00:37:20.962 align:middle line:84%
but now there's an extra
rule that the directions have

00:37:20.962 --> 00:37:22.170 align:middle line:90%
to be the same at each point.

00:37:22.170 --> 00:37:24.740 align:middle line:90%
So a very special case.

00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:26.072 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:26.072 --> 00:37:32.570 align:middle line:84%
So let's say RAD
projection of delta

00:37:32.570 --> 00:37:37.500 align:middle line:84%
is the maximum over
the usual stuff.

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:41.150 align:middle line:90%
So ET obeys our hypotheses.

00:37:41.150 --> 00:37:45.690 align:middle line:84%
E is AD regular, but
also, ET is projective.

00:37:45.690 --> 00:37:50.710 align:middle line:90%


00:37:50.710 --> 00:37:51.210 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:37:51.210 --> 00:38:00.220 align:middle line:90%


00:38:00.220 --> 00:38:07.070 align:middle line:84%
So in general, we're
taking a maximum.

00:38:07.070 --> 00:38:08.840 align:middle line:84%
And this is a
restricted maximum,

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:15.720 align:middle line:84%
so we clearly have that RAD
projective is smaller than RAD.

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:19.570 align:middle line:90%


00:38:19.570 --> 00:38:22.670 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out that they're
basically equal to each other.

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:26.110 align:middle line:90%
So let's make that a lemma.

00:38:26.110 --> 00:38:31.540 align:middle line:84%
So RAD of delta
is less than here.

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:33.040 align:middle line:84%
There is some fudge
factors, so I'll

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:34.900 align:middle line:84%
write something like
this C epsilon delta

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:35.910 align:middle line:90%
to the minus epsilon.

00:38:35.910 --> 00:38:39.340 align:middle line:90%


00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:41.132 align:middle line:90%
Actually, let me--

00:38:41.132 --> 00:38:42.590 align:middle line:84%
I won't quite say
that that's true.

00:38:42.590 --> 00:38:46.660 align:middle line:90%
But let me just say something.

00:38:46.660 --> 00:38:47.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:47.540 --> 00:38:49.180 align:middle line:84%
So here's a cool
observation based

00:38:49.180 --> 00:38:51.820 align:middle line:90%
on that diagram and that proof.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:39:01.510 align:middle line:84%
So notice that in the
submultiplicative lemma

00:39:01.510 --> 00:39:09.910 align:middle line:84%
if delta 1 equals delta 2 equals
square root of delta, then

00:39:09.910 --> 00:39:13.570 align:middle line:90%
the inner--

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:16.940 align:middle line:84%
the small ball problems
are all projective.

00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:27.203 align:middle line:90%


00:39:27.203 --> 00:39:27.703 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:27.703 --> 00:39:31.084 align:middle line:90%


00:39:31.084 --> 00:39:37.640 align:middle line:84%
So in this problem, we have a
delta scale Furstenberg problem,

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:39.910 align:middle line:84%
and we broke it up into
two pieces, a coarse piece

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:44.290 align:middle line:84%
at the large scale and a small
piece inside each small ball.

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:46.810 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that this piece
inside the small ball

00:39:46.810 --> 00:39:48.940 align:middle line:90%
is projective.

00:39:48.940 --> 00:39:50.500 align:middle line:90%
Why is it?

00:39:50.500 --> 00:39:56.110 align:middle line:84%
Well, so take one
of these points,

00:39:56.110 --> 00:39:59.500 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to look at the
directions of the red tubes

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:00.720 align:middle line:90%
going through this point.

00:40:00.720 --> 00:40:04.330 align:middle line:90%


00:40:04.330 --> 00:40:06.560 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm working
in this small ball

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:08.170 align:middle line:84%
so I can only
distinguish them up

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:11.050 align:middle line:84%
to an angle of the
square root of delta.

00:40:11.050 --> 00:40:12.920 align:middle line:90%
So what directions will they be?

00:40:12.920 --> 00:40:15.970 align:middle line:84%
They'll be the directions of
these orange tubes going out

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:17.650 align:middle line:90%
through here.

00:40:17.650 --> 00:40:21.250 align:middle line:84%
So there could well
be two long red tubes

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:24.770 align:middle line:84%
going through here that are
in the same orange tube.

00:40:24.770 --> 00:40:27.250 align:middle line:84%
But inside of this
small ball, they'll

00:40:27.250 --> 00:40:28.610 align:middle line:90%
just be on top of each other.

00:40:28.610 --> 00:40:31.360 align:middle line:84%
I won't see any
difference between them.

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:34.400 align:middle line:84%
So the directions that I'll
see within the small ball,

00:40:34.400 --> 00:40:38.500 align:middle line:84%
they just correspond
to these orange tubes.

00:40:38.500 --> 00:40:41.960 align:middle line:84%
And if I look at different
guys inside the small ball,

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:43.500 align:middle line:84%
I have the same set
of orange tubes.

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:48.190 align:middle line:90%


00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:49.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:54.010 align:middle line:90%
So that gives me an inequality.

00:40:54.010 --> 00:41:03.460 align:middle line:84%
RAD delta is bounded by RAD
delta to the 1/2 times RAD

00:41:03.460 --> 00:41:08.455 align:middle line:90%
projective delta to the 1/2.

00:41:08.455 --> 00:41:08.955 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:41:08.955 --> 00:41:10.780 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I thought
that you were

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:12.435 align:middle line:90%
writing projective [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:12.435 --> 00:41:13.310 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:41:13.310 --> 00:41:14.690 align:middle line:84%
Only the inner
one is projective.

00:41:14.690 --> 00:41:16.520 align:middle line:90%
The outer one is arbitrary.

00:41:16.520 --> 00:41:20.410 align:middle line:90%


00:41:20.410 --> 00:41:23.950 align:middle line:90%
However, we can repeat this.

00:41:23.950 --> 00:41:29.020 align:middle line:84%
So now that's bounded
by RAD delta to the 1/4,

00:41:29.020 --> 00:41:37.630 align:middle line:84%
RAD projective delta to the 1/4,
RAD projective delta to the 1/2.

00:41:37.630 --> 00:41:41.080 align:middle line:90%


00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:44.400 align:middle line:90%
And now you can keep going.

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:44.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:46.100 align:middle line:90%
So you do this many times.

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:48.340 align:middle line:84%
There will be a T
appendix left here

00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:53.330 align:middle line:84%
that still has no projective on
it, but it will be very minor.

00:41:53.330 --> 00:41:56.300 align:middle line:84%
And the rest of them
all have projective.

00:41:56.300 --> 00:42:02.200 align:middle line:84%
And so the conclusion is
that to prove the theorem,

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:04.530 align:middle line:84%
it suffices to check
the projective case.

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:13.600 align:middle line:90%


00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:17.240 align:middle line:84%
So that's a cute application
of the submultiplicative.

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:31.690 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.690 --> 00:42:32.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:38.522 align:middle line:90%


00:42:38.522 --> 00:42:41.750 align:middle line:84%
So those are a couple of cute
applications of this lemma.

00:42:41.750 --> 00:42:42.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:42:42.670 --> 00:42:45.700 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is that
an extra RAD delta

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:51.580 align:middle line:84%
to the kind of 1 over epsilon
where the delta T epsilon error

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:53.630 align:middle line:90%
term comes from?

00:42:53.630 --> 00:42:55.600 align:middle line:84%
Or is it a conditional
thing as well?

00:42:55.600 --> 00:42:57.700 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: There
are several places where

00:42:57.700 --> 00:43:00.470 align:middle line:84%
we might incur a delta T
epsilon in the final thing,

00:43:00.470 --> 00:43:01.550 align:middle line:90%
and this is one of them.

00:43:01.550 --> 00:43:03.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:05.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:08.482 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:08.482 --> 00:43:12.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's say something
big picture about trying

00:43:12.310 --> 00:43:15.370 align:middle line:90%
to prove this theorem.

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:19.460 align:middle line:84%
So we were saying yesterday that
for a while in this subject,

00:43:19.460 --> 00:43:22.810 align:middle line:84%
there were only kind of-- there
were only epsilon improvements

00:43:22.810 --> 00:43:24.410 align:middle line:90%
on some classical things.

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:26.590 align:middle line:84%
And what was very
striking to me is

00:43:26.590 --> 00:43:29.000 align:middle line:84%
to go from just making
epsilon improvements,

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:32.740 align:middle line:84%
to go to proving
the sharp theorem.

00:43:32.740 --> 00:43:35.180 align:middle line:84%
And while Pablo
Shmerkin was visiting,

00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:37.450 align:middle line:84%
I talked with him a lot
about all this stuff.

00:43:37.450 --> 00:43:40.510 align:middle line:84%
And he said to me something one
day that really stuck with me.

00:43:40.510 --> 00:43:46.971 align:middle line:90%
He said, philosophically that--

00:43:46.971 --> 00:43:48.695 align:middle line:84%
yeah, here's how I
would like to put it.

00:43:48.695 --> 00:43:51.450 align:middle line:90%


00:43:51.450 --> 00:43:55.560 align:middle line:84%
That in order to prove this
theorem, what we need to do

00:43:55.560 --> 00:44:01.890 align:middle line:84%
is make an epsilon improvement
on the submultiplicative lemma.

00:44:01.890 --> 00:44:03.390 align:middle line:84%
So let me write
that down, because I

00:44:03.390 --> 00:44:07.320 align:middle line:84%
think it's worth taking
with you out of this class.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:10.266 align:middle line:90%
So philosophy.

00:44:10.266 --> 00:44:15.960 align:middle line:90%


00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:25.890 align:middle line:84%
To prove the theorem, what we
need at epsilon improvement

00:44:25.890 --> 00:44:28.955 align:middle line:90%
on the submultiplicative lemma.

00:44:28.955 --> 00:44:35.760 align:middle line:90%


00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:36.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:42.420 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, we'd like to
say either one possibility is

00:44:42.420 --> 00:44:48.695 align:middle line:84%
that RAD square root of delta
already obeys the bound.

00:44:48.695 --> 00:44:52.590 align:middle line:90%


00:44:52.590 --> 00:44:53.340 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:44:53.340 --> 00:44:54.910 align:middle line:90%
Well, then we're happy.

00:44:54.910 --> 00:44:58.120 align:middle line:84%
And by the submultiplicative
lemma RAD of delta

00:44:58.120 --> 00:44:59.640 align:middle line:90%
also will obey the bound.

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:01.530 align:middle line:90%
So we'll be happy.

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:08.525 align:middle line:84%
Or we have-- so I'll write down
the submultiplicative lemma.

00:45:08.525 --> 00:45:17.040 align:middle line:90%


00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:20.940 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
submultiplicative lemma.

00:45:20.940 --> 00:45:25.940 align:middle line:84%
Or we have not this lemma, but
a little tiny improvement on it.

00:45:25.940 --> 00:45:32.700 align:middle line:90%


00:45:32.700 --> 00:45:33.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:35.880 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, of
course, we're happy.

00:45:35.880 --> 00:45:38.760 align:middle line:84%
And in this case,
we can iterate.

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:41.010 align:middle line:84%
And so you can think
of RAD of delta

00:45:41.010 --> 00:45:43.530 align:middle line:90%
as being some power of delta.

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:49.170 align:middle line:84%
And then every time we do
this, that power goes down,

00:45:49.170 --> 00:45:50.800 align:middle line:90%
or some negative power of delta.

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:53.120 align:middle line:84%
Every time we do this, that
power is going to go down.

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:58.140 align:middle line:90%


00:45:58.140 --> 00:46:00.400 align:middle line:84%
It will keep going down
until we get into this case

00:46:00.400 --> 00:46:01.067 align:middle line:90%
and we're happy.

00:46:01.067 --> 00:46:03.630 align:middle line:90%


00:46:03.630 --> 00:46:05.820 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:05.820 --> 00:46:08.260 align:middle line:90%
So let's illustrate that.

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:13.800 align:middle line:84%
So if, say, we
have RAD of delta--

00:46:13.800 --> 00:46:14.970 align:middle line:90%
let me write it this way.

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:16.110 align:middle line:90%
It'll be easier.

00:46:16.110 --> 00:46:18.630 align:middle line:90%
It's delta to the minus gamma.

00:46:18.630 --> 00:46:25.380 align:middle line:84%
Then we'd have RAD of delta
squared would be bounded by--

00:46:25.380 --> 00:46:29.855 align:middle line:84%
so this would give us delta to
the minus 2 gamma plus epsilon.

00:46:29.855 --> 00:46:39.300 align:middle line:90%


00:46:39.300 --> 00:46:42.240 align:middle line:90%
Then we would do this again.

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:47.160 align:middle line:84%
RAD delta to the 1/4 would be
bounded by delta to the 1/4

00:46:47.160 --> 00:46:50.430 align:middle line:84%
to the minus gamma plus
epsilon plus epsilon.

00:46:50.430 --> 00:46:54.930 align:middle line:84%
We keep going and this exponent
keeps getting better and better,

00:46:54.930 --> 00:46:57.340 align:middle line:84%
until we can't make an
epsilon improvement anymore.

00:46:57.340 --> 00:47:02.315 align:middle line:84%
So if we have this dichotomy,
then we can get the theorem.

00:47:02.315 --> 00:47:05.400 align:middle line:90%


00:47:05.400 --> 00:47:07.875 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:07.875 --> 00:47:08.375 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:47:08.375 --> 00:47:13.280 align:middle line:90%


00:47:13.280 --> 00:47:13.780 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:16.350 align:middle line:84%
So then you might
reflect, well, why

00:47:16.350 --> 00:47:19.950 align:middle line:84%
is it easier to make an epsilon
improvement kind of theorem

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:24.610 align:middle line:84%
than it is to prove a really
sharp bound straight out?

00:47:24.610 --> 00:47:27.450 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's a thought
process for that,

00:47:27.450 --> 00:47:29.150 align:middle line:84%
which is we already
have a result

00:47:29.150 --> 00:47:31.150 align:middle line:84%
and then we want to make
an epsilon improvement.

00:47:31.150 --> 00:47:32.850 align:middle line:84%
Then we say to
ourselves, what would it

00:47:32.850 --> 00:47:35.970 align:middle line:84%
look like if the result
we have is sharp?

00:47:35.970 --> 00:47:39.168 align:middle line:84%
And maybe there's a
lot of specific things

00:47:39.168 --> 00:47:41.460 align:middle line:84%
that have to happen for the
result we have to be sharp,

00:47:41.460 --> 00:47:44.440 align:middle line:90%
so we get a lot of structure.

00:47:44.440 --> 00:47:45.940 align:middle line:84%
Then we have to get
a contradiction,

00:47:45.940 --> 00:47:48.010 align:middle line:84%
and that shows you can do
just a little bit better.

00:47:48.010 --> 00:47:49.593 align:middle line:84%
So that's why that
epsilon improvement

00:47:49.593 --> 00:47:54.330 align:middle line:84%
result is easier than just
getting a great bound straight

00:47:54.330 --> 00:47:55.920 align:middle line:90%
away.

00:47:55.920 --> 00:47:58.530 align:middle line:84%
So if we go back to
Bergen's projection theorem

00:47:58.530 --> 00:48:00.000 align:middle line:84%
and we tried to
make it an epsilon

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.200 align:middle line:84%
improvement in a
projection theorem,

00:48:02.200 --> 00:48:04.510 align:middle line:84%
well, we didn't say
this at the time,

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:06.030 align:middle line:84%
but it might have
been good to say.

00:48:06.030 --> 00:48:07.090 align:middle line:90%
What would it be like?

00:48:07.090 --> 00:48:09.640 align:middle line:84%
What would it mean if the
bound we have so far is sharp?

00:48:09.640 --> 00:48:11.620 align:middle line:84%
It would mean we have this
structure and that structure,

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:13.078 align:middle line:84%
and eventually, we
have this subset

00:48:13.078 --> 00:48:14.940 align:middle line:84%
that is almost
closed under addition

00:48:14.940 --> 00:48:19.380 align:middle line:84%
and almost closed
under multiplication.

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:20.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:22.873 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is we are going
to try to do the same thing.

00:48:22.873 --> 00:48:24.540 align:middle line:84%
We're going to think
about what would it

00:48:24.540 --> 00:48:27.570 align:middle line:84%
mean if the submultiplicative
lemma was sharp.

00:48:27.570 --> 00:48:29.460 align:middle line:84%
We're going to see
that it just means

00:48:29.460 --> 00:48:31.620 align:middle line:84%
the set has to have
a lot of structure,

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:33.640 align:middle line:90%
and eventually, we'll get down.

00:48:33.640 --> 00:48:37.680 align:middle line:84%
Maybe not today, but
eventually Orponen and Shmerkin

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:40.230 align:middle line:84%
got down to the
structures, got down

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:47.730 align:middle line:84%
to the Bergen projection
theorem and got a contradiction.

00:48:47.730 --> 00:48:49.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:49.170 --> 00:48:49.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:49.840 --> 00:48:51.540 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk
about what would it

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:54.185 align:middle line:84%
mean if the submultiplicative
lemma is sharp.

00:48:54.185 --> 00:49:44.430 align:middle line:90%


00:49:44.430 --> 00:49:45.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:45.160 --> 00:49:49.000 align:middle line:84%
So let me draw a couple
pictures for you.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
pictures corresponds

00:49:51.060 --> 00:49:54.150 align:middle line:84%
to the submultiplicative lemma
is sharp and the other one,

00:49:54.150 --> 00:49:55.220 align:middle line:90%
it's not.

00:49:55.220 --> 00:50:04.860 align:middle line:90%


00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:08.975 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have some fat
balls in a fat tube.

00:50:08.975 --> 00:50:14.190 align:middle line:90%


00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:19.950 align:middle line:84%
And then in each fat
tube, in each fat ball,

00:50:19.950 --> 00:50:23.450 align:middle line:90%
we have some little balls.

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:26.410 align:middle line:84%
And the little balls
are in little tubes.

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:32.300 align:middle line:90%


00:50:32.300 --> 00:50:36.300 align:middle line:84%
So there's your typical little
tube OK, in each of these balls,

00:50:36.300 --> 00:50:37.100 align:middle line:90%
there are some--

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:39.595 align:middle line:84%
in each of these fat balls,
there are some little balls.

00:50:39.595 --> 00:50:47.060 align:middle line:90%


00:50:47.060 --> 00:50:47.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:47.560 --> 00:50:56.119 align:middle line:90%


00:50:56.119 --> 00:50:59.060 align:middle line:84%
So in this scenario,
in this picture,

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:04.440 align:middle line:84%
would the submultiplicative
lemma be sharp or not sharp?

00:51:04.440 --> 00:51:04.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:04.940 --> 00:51:07.970 align:middle line:90%
Stand next to the picture.

00:51:07.970 --> 00:51:10.340 align:middle line:84%
This picture, would the
submultiplicative lemma

00:51:10.340 --> 00:51:12.190 align:middle line:90%
be sharp or not sharp?

00:51:12.190 --> 00:51:16.573 align:middle line:90%


00:51:16.573 --> 00:51:17.990 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I don't
think it's sharp

00:51:17.990 --> 00:51:24.351 align:middle line:84%
because there's just one
tube for the coarser scale.

00:51:24.351 --> 00:51:28.440 align:middle line:84%
There's several tubes
for the fine scale.

00:51:28.440 --> 00:51:31.170 align:middle line:90%


00:51:31.170 --> 00:51:31.920 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:51:31.920 --> 00:51:34.790 align:middle line:84%
So let me clarify what
this is a picture of.

00:51:34.790 --> 00:51:37.950 align:middle line:84%
So there are many
coarse scale tubes,

00:51:37.950 --> 00:51:40.490 align:middle line:84%
but I just drew one
of them, and I'm just

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:43.160 align:middle line:84%
drawing what's happening
inside of one of them.

00:51:43.160 --> 00:51:46.730 align:middle line:84%
So inside of that one coarse
tube, this is what we see.

00:51:46.730 --> 00:51:48.560 align:middle line:90%
Based on this is the--

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:51.353 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So there's
only one fine scale tube?

00:51:51.353 --> 00:51:53.520 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: There could
be more fine scale tubes,

00:51:53.520 --> 00:51:55.310 align:middle line:90%
but this is a typical one.

00:51:55.310 --> 00:51:57.990 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so there are many orange
tubes and many red tubes,

00:51:57.990 --> 00:52:04.200 align:middle line:84%
but I'm drawing only one of
each to focus our attention.

00:52:04.200 --> 00:52:09.530 align:middle line:90%


00:52:09.530 --> 00:52:10.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:10.050 --> 00:52:11.990 align:middle line:84%
So let's review for
a second the proof

00:52:11.990 --> 00:52:15.090 align:middle line:84%
of the submultiplicative lemma,
because it's really important.

00:52:15.090 --> 00:52:17.180 align:middle line:84%
And maybe we'll go
in a little deeper,

00:52:17.180 --> 00:52:19.640 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll try
to show it again.

00:52:19.640 --> 00:52:20.921 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:20.921 --> 00:52:24.210 align:middle line:84%
So our goal is to
estimate RAD of delta,

00:52:24.210 --> 00:52:27.920 align:middle line:84%
which is the number of
delta balls per delta tube.

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:31.440 align:middle line:84%
So I picked a delta tube
like this red one here.

00:52:31.440 --> 00:52:33.900 align:middle line:84%
I'll have to estimate the
number of delta balls in it.

00:52:33.900 --> 00:52:38.930 align:middle line:84%
First I estimate the number of
fat balls that it intersects.

00:52:38.930 --> 00:52:41.600 align:middle line:84%
Then I multiply that by
the number of delta balls

00:52:41.600 --> 00:52:45.020 align:middle line:84%
that it intersects
within each fat ball.

00:52:45.020 --> 00:52:48.410 align:middle line:90%
And that was my bound.

00:52:48.410 --> 00:52:51.690 align:middle line:84%
And then each one of those
things, I bounded by induction

00:52:51.690 --> 00:52:53.720 align:middle line:90%
and I got those two numbers.

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:54.270 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:52:54.270 --> 00:52:59.690 align:middle line:84%
So if I take a particular
fat tube, and inside of it

00:52:59.690 --> 00:53:02.510 align:middle line:84%
a particular thin
tube and I see this,

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:04.225 align:middle line:90%
would that argument be sharp?

00:53:04.225 --> 00:53:06.860 align:middle line:90%


00:53:06.860 --> 00:53:07.720 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:53:07.720 --> 00:53:08.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:08.220 --> 00:53:10.760 align:middle line:84%
So the suggestion is
that this is not sharp

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:16.040 align:middle line:84%
because inside of this red
tube, most of the fat balls

00:53:16.040 --> 00:53:18.680 align:middle line:90%
are contributed nothing.

00:53:18.680 --> 00:53:23.150 align:middle line:84%
Only this one fat
ball is contributing.

00:53:23.150 --> 00:53:25.190 align:middle line:84%
And it would be
sharp if the number

00:53:25.190 --> 00:53:29.257 align:middle line:84%
of delta balls in the fat
ball was the number of--

00:53:29.257 --> 00:53:31.340 align:middle line:84%
sorry, the number of delta
balls in the delta tube

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:34.220 align:middle line:84%
was the number of fat
balls times the number

00:53:34.220 --> 00:53:36.860 align:middle line:90%
of delta balls in one of them.

00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:37.920 align:middle line:90%
So let me show.

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:40.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is not sharp, and let
me draw the one that's sharp.

00:53:40.530 --> 00:53:41.820 align:middle line:90%
You'll see the difference.

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:42.805 align:middle line:90%
This is not sharp.

00:53:42.805 --> 00:54:10.460 align:middle line:90%


00:54:10.460 --> 00:54:14.635 align:middle line:84%
Delta tube should
look like this.

00:54:14.635 --> 00:54:20.540 align:middle line:90%


00:54:20.540 --> 00:54:21.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:25.220 align:middle line:84%
So the delta tube should
intersect a bunch of fat balls.

00:54:25.220 --> 00:54:28.380 align:middle line:84%
It should intersect that many
fat balls, as many as possible.

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:31.670 align:middle line:84%
And inside each one
of them, it should

00:54:31.670 --> 00:54:34.183 align:middle line:84%
intersect a lot of delta
balls, as many as possible.

00:54:34.183 --> 00:54:36.350 align:middle line:84%
That's what it takes for
the submultiplicative lemma

00:54:36.350 --> 00:54:38.600 align:middle line:90%
to be sharp.

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:40.340 align:middle line:90%
So it should look like this.

00:54:40.340 --> 00:54:41.560 align:middle line:90%
So this is sharp.

00:54:41.560 --> 00:54:54.860 align:middle line:90%


00:54:54.860 --> 00:54:55.850 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:54:55.850 --> 00:54:58.783 align:middle line:84%
And this is a kind
of striking picture.

00:54:58.783 --> 00:55:15.140 align:middle line:90%


00:55:15.140 --> 00:55:21.470 align:middle line:84%
So in this ball, these points
are in just a few tubes

00:55:21.470 --> 00:55:22.890 align:middle line:90%
in a certain direction.

00:55:22.890 --> 00:55:25.670 align:middle line:84%
You could also imagine we're
in the projective case.

00:55:25.670 --> 00:55:30.800 align:middle line:84%
And in these other balls, the
points are in those same tubes.

00:55:30.800 --> 00:55:32.007 align:middle line:90%
It goes all the way across.

00:55:32.007 --> 00:55:34.340 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the balls don't
have to look exactly the same

00:55:34.340 --> 00:55:36.940 align:middle line:84%
as each other, so maybe a
better picture might be like so.

00:55:36.940 --> 00:55:40.550 align:middle line:90%


00:55:40.550 --> 00:55:42.955 align:middle line:84%
But the tubes are
exactly the same.

00:55:42.955 --> 00:55:46.470 align:middle line:90%


00:55:46.470 --> 00:55:46.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:46.970 --> 00:55:55.490 align:middle line:90%


00:55:55.490 --> 00:55:56.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:56.510 --> 00:56:06.030 align:middle line:90%
So let me pause.

00:56:06.030 --> 00:56:08.970 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to erase a little bit
to make some space around here.

00:56:08.970 --> 00:56:10.430 align:middle line:90%
Is that OK with everybody?

00:56:10.430 --> 00:56:12.840 align:middle line:84%
That if the submultiplicative
lemma is sharp,

00:56:12.840 --> 00:56:16.030 align:middle line:84%
it has to look like
this, not like that.

00:56:16.030 --> 00:56:17.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:17.170 --> 00:56:17.713 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:56:17.713 --> 00:56:19.380 align:middle line:84%
So let's erase around
here a little bit.

00:56:19.380 --> 00:56:28.630 align:middle line:90%


00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:29.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:29.620 --> 00:56:33.330 align:middle line:84%
So we already reduced
to the projective case.

00:56:33.330 --> 00:56:37.180 align:middle line:90%


00:56:37.180 --> 00:56:40.820 align:middle line:84%
So let's say D is the
set of directions,

00:56:40.820 --> 00:56:44.050 align:middle line:84%
which is the same everywhere
of our projections.

00:56:44.050 --> 00:56:53.920 align:middle line:84%
And so D is a delta
S set in S. And here

00:56:53.920 --> 00:56:56.120 align:middle line:90%
I fixed a typical fat tube.

00:56:56.120 --> 00:57:00.075 align:middle line:84%
So here's a typical
root delta tube.

00:57:00.075 --> 00:57:04.060 align:middle line:90%


00:57:04.060 --> 00:57:06.610 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to look
at the angles that

00:57:06.610 --> 00:57:08.205 align:middle line:90%
are within this fat tube.

00:57:08.205 --> 00:57:15.130 align:middle line:90%


00:57:15.130 --> 00:57:17.720 align:middle line:90%
So here's our circle.

00:57:17.720 --> 00:57:20.540 align:middle line:84%
And there's a little
range of angles here.

00:57:20.540 --> 00:57:22.450 align:middle line:84%
This is a delta to the--
there's theta, which

00:57:22.450 --> 00:57:24.460 align:middle line:90%
is a delta to the one half arc.

00:57:24.460 --> 00:57:26.640 align:middle line:84%
That corresponds
to the fat tube.

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:35.620 align:middle line:90%


00:57:35.620 --> 00:57:37.396 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:37.396 --> 00:57:43.310 align:middle line:84%
And so D is some delta
set, delta SC set in here.

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:49.400 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that C is
D intersected with theta.

00:57:49.400 --> 00:57:51.050 align:middle line:90%
So it's just these directions.

00:57:51.050 --> 00:57:55.241 align:middle line:90%


00:57:55.241 --> 00:57:55.741 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:55.741 --> 00:57:59.980 align:middle line:90%


00:57:59.980 --> 00:58:05.500 align:middle line:84%
So the red tubes correspond to
one of the directions in theta.

00:58:05.500 --> 00:58:06.730 align:middle line:90%
So this one there.

00:58:06.730 --> 00:58:08.740 align:middle line:90%
Red tube.

00:58:08.740 --> 00:58:13.040 align:middle line:84%
And so when I project this
set in the red direction,

00:58:13.040 --> 00:58:14.750 align:middle line:90%
I just get a small set.

00:58:14.750 --> 00:58:16.490 align:middle line:84%
But it's not just
the red direction.

00:58:16.490 --> 00:58:19.340 align:middle line:84%
I could draw some other
directions inside of the tube

00:58:19.340 --> 00:58:20.020 align:middle line:90%
also.

00:58:20.020 --> 00:58:22.000 align:middle line:90%
Let me do one more.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:25.420 align:middle line:84%
I'll take here a blue
direction inside of here.

00:58:25.420 --> 00:58:27.590 align:middle line:84%
So I draw the tubes
in the blue direction.

00:58:27.590 --> 00:58:28.820 align:middle line:90%
What would it look like?

00:58:28.820 --> 00:58:31.370 align:middle line:84%
I think I need to make this
picture come out nicely.

00:58:31.370 --> 00:58:33.033 align:middle line:90%
I need to add a few more points.

00:58:33.033 --> 00:58:38.470 align:middle line:90%


00:58:38.470 --> 00:58:40.185 align:middle line:90%
So that'd be one more red tube.

00:58:40.185 --> 00:58:42.485 align:middle line:90%


00:58:42.485 --> 00:58:42.985 align:middle line:90%
Oops.

00:58:42.985 --> 00:58:47.110 align:middle line:90%


00:58:47.110 --> 00:58:49.910 align:middle line:84%
And now I'll draw a
typical blue tube.

00:58:49.910 --> 00:58:54.520 align:middle line:84%
The blue tube also manages to
intersect our points a lot,

00:58:54.520 --> 00:58:56.535 align:middle line:90%
so it should look like this.

00:58:56.535 --> 00:59:03.255 align:middle line:90%


00:59:03.255 --> 00:59:04.630 align:middle line:84%
I don't think I
can draw any more

00:59:04.630 --> 00:59:07.830 align:middle line:84%
without making a complete
mess, but you get the idea.

00:59:07.830 --> 00:59:10.480 align:middle line:90%


00:59:10.480 --> 00:59:13.790 align:middle line:84%
So the blue tube passes
through all these balls also,

00:59:13.790 --> 00:59:16.610 align:middle line:84%
and each time the blue
tube passes through a ball,

00:59:16.610 --> 00:59:22.060 align:middle line:84%
it manages to line up
with one of the red tubes.

00:59:22.060 --> 00:59:22.900 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:59:22.900 --> 00:59:24.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:24.740 --> 00:59:28.750 align:middle line:84%
So we have a kind
of special situation

00:59:28.750 --> 00:59:31.690 align:middle line:90%
here with a product structure.

00:59:31.690 --> 00:59:35.110 align:middle line:90%
So what is our set?

00:59:35.110 --> 00:59:40.570 align:middle line:84%
So let's say over here
these dots, the projection

00:59:40.570 --> 00:59:43.420 align:middle line:84%
in the red direction,
let's call this A.

00:59:43.420 --> 00:59:47.710 align:middle line:84%
And then down here,
we can make a set

00:59:47.710 --> 00:59:51.850 align:middle line:84%
that illustrates where the
fat balls are in the fat tube.

00:59:51.850 --> 01:00:03.910 align:middle line:84%
Let's call that B. And so what
we see is that for every C in C,

01:00:03.910 --> 01:00:08.140 align:middle line:84%
the projection in
the C direction--

01:00:08.140 --> 01:00:09.760 align:middle line:90%
or I'll write it this way.

01:00:09.760 --> 01:00:15.010 align:middle line:84%
A plus CB-- that's the
projection in the C direction--

01:00:15.010 --> 01:00:23.680 align:middle line:90%
is not much bigger than A.

01:00:23.680 --> 01:00:26.720 align:middle line:84%
The projection in every one
of these directions is small.

01:00:26.720 --> 01:00:28.840 align:middle line:84%
They're all about the
same as each other.

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:31.870 align:middle line:84%
A was the projection
in the red direction.

01:00:31.870 --> 01:00:33.530 align:middle line:90%
The blue one is just as good.

01:00:33.530 --> 01:00:43.780 align:middle line:84%
So A plus CB should be not
much bigger than A. OK.

01:00:43.780 --> 01:00:47.740 align:middle line:90%


01:00:47.740 --> 01:00:48.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:48.350 --> 01:00:51.255 align:middle line:84%
So let me summarize
what we have seen here.

01:00:51.255 --> 01:01:17.680 align:middle line:90%


01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:19.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:19.390 --> 01:01:28.343 align:middle line:84%
So f submultiplicative
lemma is sharp.

01:01:28.343 --> 01:01:32.620 align:middle line:90%


01:01:32.620 --> 01:01:39.340 align:middle line:84%
Then we get sets A
and B and C, which

01:01:39.340 --> 01:01:42.370 align:middle line:90%
are subsets of real numbers.

01:01:42.370 --> 01:01:51.315 align:middle line:84%
And in the main case,
A is a delta A A set.

01:01:51.315 --> 01:01:54.160 align:middle line:90%


01:01:54.160 --> 01:01:56.530 align:middle line:90%
It's rho A set.

01:01:56.530 --> 01:02:03.510 align:middle line:84%
Size of A is like rho to the
minus A. B is a rho B set.

01:02:03.510 --> 01:02:10.260 align:middle line:84%
Size of B is like rho to the
minus B. C is a rho C set.

01:02:10.260 --> 01:02:13.830 align:middle line:84%
Size of C is like
rho to the minus C.

01:02:13.830 --> 01:02:30.290 align:middle line:84%
And for every C in C, A plus CB
is not very much bigger than A.

01:02:30.290 --> 01:02:30.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:30.790 --> 01:02:34.380 align:middle line:84%
Now the size of A and B and
C can all be traced back

01:02:34.380 --> 01:02:37.920 align:middle line:90%
to the numbers in our problem.

01:02:37.920 --> 01:02:47.280 align:middle line:84%
And we find that if A is
smaller than B plus C, that's

01:02:47.280 --> 01:02:53.630 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to saying that RAD
is square root of delta is good.

01:02:53.630 --> 01:02:54.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:54.130 --> 01:02:54.630 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:02:54.630 --> 01:02:58.140 align:middle line:84%
A is larger than B
plus C, then that means

01:02:58.140 --> 01:02:59.680 align:middle line:90%
you do a boring computation.

01:02:59.680 --> 01:03:03.540 align:middle line:90%


01:03:03.540 --> 01:03:08.040 align:middle line:84%
So there's an intermediate
result. Maybe I'll

01:03:08.040 --> 01:03:12.120 align:middle line:84%
call it a key lemma, which
is called the ABC sum product

01:03:12.120 --> 01:03:19.350 align:middle line:84%
lemma, which just goes into
this paper of Orponen-Shmerkin.

01:03:19.350 --> 01:03:26.190 align:middle line:84%
And it says if you have all
of this stuff then, indeed,

01:03:26.190 --> 01:03:42.120 align:middle line:90%
A is bigger than B plus C. Yeah?

01:03:42.120 --> 01:03:43.680 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: What does good mean?

01:03:43.680 --> 01:03:46.400 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Good means
that it obeys the theorem.

01:03:46.400 --> 01:03:53.580 align:middle line:90%


01:03:53.580 --> 01:03:54.760 align:middle line:90%
So the theorem is up there.

01:03:54.760 --> 01:03:59.790 align:middle line:84%
So it's smaller than
the maximum of 1

01:03:59.790 --> 01:04:07.110 align:middle line:84%
and root delta to the minus
T over 2 plus S over 2

01:04:07.110 --> 01:04:13.410 align:middle line:84%
and root delta to the 1 minus
T. So if that's the case,

01:04:13.410 --> 01:04:14.190 align:middle line:90%
we're happy.

01:04:14.190 --> 01:04:16.670 align:middle line:90%
And otherwise-- yeah, OK.

01:04:16.670 --> 01:04:21.450 align:middle line:90%


01:04:21.450 --> 01:04:24.618 align:middle line:84%
OK, so let's go back to
our general strategy,

01:04:24.618 --> 01:04:25.660 align:middle line:90%
our big picture strategy.

01:04:25.660 --> 01:04:28.500 align:middle line:84%
We would like to prove this
theorem, that RAD of delta

01:04:28.500 --> 01:04:30.750 align:middle line:90%
is always smaller than that.

01:04:30.750 --> 01:04:33.300 align:middle line:84%
And we considered the
submultiplicative lemma,

01:04:33.300 --> 01:04:34.960 align:middle line:84%
which doesn't give
us the theorem yet,

01:04:34.960 --> 01:04:37.800 align:middle line:90%
but it's an important tool.

01:04:37.800 --> 01:04:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And we'd like to say if
we can have an epsilon

01:04:46.980 --> 01:04:50.100 align:middle line:84%
improvement in the
submultiplicative lemma, then

01:04:50.100 --> 01:04:50.920 align:middle line:90%
that's great.

01:04:50.920 --> 01:04:53.350 align:middle line:84%
We go to the next scale
and we have a better bound.

01:04:53.350 --> 01:04:56.550 align:middle line:84%
So you keep doing
that until you stop.

01:04:56.550 --> 01:04:59.040 align:middle line:84%
And we must stop in
a situation where

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:01.980 align:middle line:84%
there's no more, where the
submultiplicative lemma becomes

01:05:01.980 --> 01:05:03.490 align:middle line:90%
sharp.

01:05:03.490 --> 01:05:04.990 align:middle line:84%
Maybe that's a
better way to say it.

01:05:04.990 --> 01:05:06.532 align:middle line:84%
We have this
submultiplicative lemma.

01:05:06.532 --> 01:05:07.890 align:middle line:90%
We use it.

01:05:07.890 --> 01:05:09.820 align:middle line:90%
It's either sharp or it's not.

01:05:09.820 --> 01:05:13.590 align:middle line:84%
If it's not, we get a
nicer exponent at delta

01:05:13.590 --> 01:05:15.390 align:middle line:90%
squared than we did at delta.

01:05:15.390 --> 01:05:16.870 align:middle line:90%
We keep doing that.

01:05:16.870 --> 01:05:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And the exponent is not going
to keep getting better forever,

01:05:19.540 --> 01:05:22.123 align:middle line:84%
so we stop at some moment where
the submultiplicative lemma is

01:05:22.123 --> 01:05:24.960 align:middle line:90%
basically sharp.

01:05:24.960 --> 01:05:27.960 align:middle line:84%
But the fact that the
submultiplicative lemma is sharp

01:05:27.960 --> 01:05:30.220 align:middle line:90%
gives us a lot of structure.

01:05:30.220 --> 01:05:34.380 align:middle line:84%
It gives us the structure
of being projective,

01:05:34.380 --> 01:05:38.050 align:middle line:84%
and it gives us this kind
of product structure.

01:05:38.050 --> 01:05:39.900 align:middle line:84%
And it leads us to
this problem, which

01:05:39.900 --> 01:05:41.760 align:middle line:84%
looks a lot like
additive combinatorics

01:05:41.760 --> 01:05:44.190 align:middle line:84%
and which is very
special problem compared

01:05:44.190 --> 01:05:47.745 align:middle line:90%
to our original setup.

01:05:47.745 --> 01:05:50.920 align:middle line:84%
And then the bound we need
to prove for this problem,

01:05:50.920 --> 01:05:52.770 align:middle line:84%
if you just unwind
the computation,

01:05:52.770 --> 01:05:56.160 align:middle line:84%
we need to prove this
bound for this problem.

01:05:56.160 --> 01:05:58.020 align:middle line:84%
If you unwind it,
it will tell us

01:05:58.020 --> 01:06:01.175 align:middle line:84%
that RAD obeys
the desired bound.

01:06:01.175 --> 01:06:04.170 align:middle line:90%


01:06:04.170 --> 01:06:04.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:06:04.920 --> 01:06:07.020 align:middle line:90%
I guess rho is also--

01:06:07.020 --> 01:06:09.565 align:middle line:84%
rho Here is square
root of delta.

01:06:09.565 --> 01:06:10.065 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:06:10.065 --> 01:06:22.710 align:middle line:90%


01:06:22.710 --> 01:06:24.810 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:25.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:25.870 --> 01:06:30.840 align:middle line:84%
So this situation is now
a lot more structured

01:06:30.840 --> 01:06:32.920 align:middle line:90%
than what we started with.

01:06:32.920 --> 01:06:37.600 align:middle line:84%
And it looks reminiscent
of additive combinatorics,

01:06:37.600 --> 01:06:40.060 align:middle line:84%
maybe of Bergen projection
theorem and so on.

01:06:40.060 --> 01:06:44.880 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, they were able to
deal with it with that toolkit.

01:06:44.880 --> 01:06:46.850 align:middle line:90%
I could say a little--

01:06:46.850 --> 01:06:48.580 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to write
too many equations,

01:06:48.580 --> 01:06:49.872 align:middle line:90%
so I won't say the whole thing.

01:06:49.872 --> 01:06:51.510 align:middle line:84%
I could say a
little bit about it.

01:06:51.510 --> 01:06:55.350 align:middle line:84%
But I think that what
we've done so far

01:06:55.350 --> 01:06:58.740 align:middle line:84%
is what I feel is
most worth remembering

01:06:58.740 --> 01:07:00.540 align:middle line:90%
about the proof of this theorem.

01:07:00.540 --> 01:07:03.840 align:middle line:84%
So let's pause here and see
if people have any questions

01:07:03.840 --> 01:07:04.870 align:middle line:90%
or comments about it.

01:07:04.870 --> 01:07:28.290 align:middle line:90%


01:07:28.290 --> 01:07:30.900 align:middle line:90%
Let me summarize it.

01:07:30.900 --> 01:07:34.170 align:middle line:84%
So the AD regular
case is special

01:07:34.170 --> 01:07:37.510 align:middle line:84%
because all the scales
are related to each other.

01:07:37.510 --> 01:07:41.490 align:middle line:84%
And so we can break it up into
problems at different scales

01:07:41.490 --> 01:07:42.960 align:middle line:90%
and put them together.

01:07:42.960 --> 01:07:45.210 align:middle line:84%
And by doing that,
we get problems

01:07:45.210 --> 01:07:46.570 align:middle line:90%
that are somewhat nicer.

01:07:46.570 --> 01:07:48.600 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, if
we look at the problem

01:07:48.600 --> 01:07:51.120 align:middle line:84%
in a small ball instead
of the original problem,

01:07:51.120 --> 01:07:54.530 align:middle line:84%
it becomes nicer because the
directions through any point

01:07:54.530 --> 01:07:55.723 align:middle line:90%
are the same.

01:07:55.723 --> 01:07:57.140 align:middle line:84%
For any two points,
the directions

01:07:57.140 --> 01:07:59.000 align:middle line:84%
are the same because they
correspond to the directions

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:00.540 align:middle line:90%
of the fat tube through there.

01:08:00.540 --> 01:08:04.760 align:middle line:84%
So this already made
it a little bit nicer.

01:08:04.760 --> 01:08:09.410 align:middle line:84%
Then, moreover, in order for
the submultiplicative lemma

01:08:09.410 --> 01:08:11.160 align:middle line:90%
to be sharp--

01:08:11.160 --> 01:08:13.320 align:middle line:84%
so if the submultiplicative
lemma is not sharp,

01:08:13.320 --> 01:08:15.680 align:middle line:84%
then you just keep
going down scales

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:17.513 align:middle line:84%
and you keep getting
better exponents.

01:08:17.513 --> 01:08:20.180 align:middle line:84%
And eventually that has to stop
when the submultiplicative lemma

01:08:20.180 --> 01:08:21.649 align:middle line:90%
is sharp.

01:08:21.649 --> 01:08:23.399 align:middle line:84%
When the submultiplicative
lemma is sharp,

01:08:23.399 --> 01:08:26.660 align:middle line:84%
there's even more structure
because these different balls

01:08:26.660 --> 01:08:29.090 align:middle line:90%
have to talk to each other.

01:08:29.090 --> 01:08:34.109 align:middle line:84%
And so if you see in this
ball, you see a tube here,

01:08:34.109 --> 01:08:38.569 align:middle line:84%
then you have to see a tube in
the same place in that ball.

01:08:38.569 --> 01:08:40.580 align:middle line:84%
And that means that
this set of points

01:08:40.580 --> 01:08:43.790 align:middle line:90%
has kind of a product structure.

01:08:43.790 --> 01:08:46.580 align:middle line:84%
And in particular,
what's literally

01:08:46.580 --> 01:08:48.710 align:middle line:90%
true is if you take these--

01:08:48.710 --> 01:08:50.130 align:middle line:90%
well, sorry.

01:08:50.130 --> 01:08:53.779 align:middle line:84%
So if you take the set
of red tubes in this ball

01:08:53.779 --> 01:08:55.859 align:middle line:84%
and then in this ball
and then in this ball,

01:08:55.859 --> 01:08:59.820 align:middle line:84%
that is a product
which is very helpful.

01:08:59.820 --> 01:09:00.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:00.320 --> 01:09:02.830 align:middle line:90%


01:09:02.830 --> 01:09:03.330 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:09:03.330 --> 01:09:10.609 align:middle line:84%
So the AD regular case allows us
to restrict to a situation which

01:09:10.609 --> 01:09:13.700 align:middle line:84%
has a lot more structure,
and it restricts

01:09:13.700 --> 01:09:17.390 align:middle line:84%
to this lemma about
projections of a product set.

01:09:17.390 --> 01:09:18.761 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:18.761 --> 01:09:20.300 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So in
the argument, I can

01:09:20.300 --> 01:09:24.830 align:middle line:84%
continue until the
submultiplicative lemma

01:09:24.830 --> 01:09:26.180 align:middle line:90%
is sharp.

01:09:26.180 --> 01:09:28.430 align:middle line:84%
How do you know that kind
of sharpness corresponds

01:09:28.430 --> 01:09:33.380 align:middle line:84%
to the delta T epsilon
factor, rather than just

01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:36.369 align:middle line:90%
kind of something much smaller?

01:09:36.369 --> 01:09:38.630 align:middle line:90%
Because it seems like--

01:09:38.630 --> 01:09:42.470 align:middle line:84%
I don't understand how you can
get a quantitative bound out

01:09:42.470 --> 01:09:46.112 align:middle line:84%
of the more qualitative proof
by contradiction or-- yeah.

01:09:46.112 --> 01:09:46.945 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:09:46.945 --> 01:09:47.445 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:47.445 --> 01:09:49.189 align:middle line:84%
So this question
is about keeping

01:09:49.189 --> 01:09:51.180 align:middle line:90%
track of the small parameters.

01:09:51.180 --> 01:09:56.600 align:middle line:84%
So every time I apply the
submultiplicative lemma,

01:09:56.600 --> 01:09:59.490 align:middle line:84%
I was using the word
sharp or not sharp.

01:09:59.490 --> 01:10:01.650 align:middle line:84%
But of course, there's
some kind of a gray zone

01:10:01.650 --> 01:10:03.510 align:middle line:84%
and I have to decide
where I'm going to cut.

01:10:03.510 --> 01:10:08.960 align:middle line:84%
What am I going to consider to
be sharp and what is not sharp?

01:10:08.960 --> 01:10:13.676 align:middle line:90%
And then, in this analysis--

01:10:13.676 --> 01:10:18.440 align:middle line:90%


01:10:18.440 --> 01:10:19.310 align:middle line:90%
yeah, OK.

01:10:19.310 --> 01:10:21.350 align:middle line:84%
Actually, so in order
for this to stop

01:10:21.350 --> 01:10:23.210 align:middle line:84%
in a reasonable
amount of time, I'm

01:10:23.210 --> 01:10:27.260 align:middle line:84%
going to have to have a cutoff
that's a tiny power of delta.

01:10:27.260 --> 01:10:32.780 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise this would go on
too long, wouldn't work.

01:10:32.780 --> 01:10:41.210 align:middle line:84%
So I would say, so what would
the definition of sharp be?

01:10:41.210 --> 01:10:41.935 align:middle line:90%
Let's do that.

01:10:41.935 --> 01:10:49.220 align:middle line:90%


01:10:49.220 --> 01:10:49.910 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:10:49.910 --> 01:10:53.330 align:middle line:90%
Let's get rid of this set.

01:10:53.330 --> 01:10:59.450 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to use the
submultiplicative lemma

01:10:59.450 --> 01:11:00.316 align:middle line:90%
repeatedly.

01:11:00.316 --> 01:11:04.070 align:middle line:90%


01:11:04.070 --> 01:11:08.900 align:middle line:84%
And so if our AD
of delta is bigger

01:11:08.900 --> 01:11:14.850 align:middle line:84%
than, I need to put something
here, RAD of root delta squared.

01:11:14.850 --> 01:11:18.320 align:middle line:84%
And here I'm going to put
delta to the epsilon 0

01:11:18.320 --> 01:11:20.900 align:middle line:84%
where epsilon 0 is
a tiny parameter.

01:11:20.900 --> 01:11:23.960 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm going to
call this sharp

01:11:23.960 --> 01:11:26.776 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to
stop and analyze.

01:11:26.776 --> 01:11:29.450 align:middle line:90%


01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:32.930 align:middle line:84%
And the other possibility
is that RAD of delta

01:11:32.930 --> 01:11:36.020 align:middle line:84%
is less than delta
to the epsilon 0

01:11:36.020 --> 01:11:40.050 align:middle line:90%
RAD of root delta squared.

01:11:40.050 --> 01:11:43.910 align:middle line:84%
And here I'm making
progress, so I'll keep going.

01:11:43.910 --> 01:11:47.300 align:middle line:90%
So this is the not sharp case.

01:11:47.300 --> 01:11:48.550 align:middle line:90%
So now I'll keep going.

01:11:48.550 --> 01:11:52.790 align:middle line:90%


01:11:52.790 --> 01:11:53.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:53.780 --> 01:11:56.930 align:middle line:84%
So that's if we're more
careful about what is sharp

01:11:56.930 --> 01:11:58.430 align:middle line:90%
and not sharp.

01:11:58.430 --> 01:11:59.220 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:11:59.220 --> 01:12:04.310 align:middle line:84%
So here, if I keep going every
time I make a definite amount

01:12:04.310 --> 01:12:07.940 align:middle line:84%
of progress, and so this
actually cannot keep going

01:12:07.940 --> 01:12:10.520 align:middle line:84%
forever because eventually the
exponents would be negative

01:12:10.520 --> 01:12:11.400 align:middle line:90%
instead of positive.

01:12:11.400 --> 01:12:14.120 align:middle line:84%
So it will stop, so
we will end up here.

01:12:14.120 --> 01:12:16.560 align:middle line:84%
Once we end up here, we have
to analyze the sharp case.

01:12:16.560 --> 01:12:19.860 align:middle line:84%
And we do have to remember,
it wasn't perfectly sharp,

01:12:19.860 --> 01:12:23.630 align:middle line:84%
but we had a fudge factor
of a tiny power of delta.

01:12:23.630 --> 01:12:27.470 align:middle line:84%
And that complicates all the
pictures that we have drawn.

01:12:27.470 --> 01:12:31.640 align:middle line:84%
So in this picture
here, this tube

01:12:31.640 --> 01:12:33.480 align:middle line:90%
goes through many fat tubes.

01:12:33.480 --> 01:12:37.760 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have to have many
delta balls in all of them.

01:12:37.760 --> 01:12:40.790 align:middle line:84%
It has to have many delta
balls in a fraction, like delta

01:12:40.790 --> 01:12:42.740 align:middle line:90%
to the epsilon fraction of them.

01:12:42.740 --> 01:12:45.920 align:middle line:84%
So it makes the picture a
little bit more complicated.

01:12:45.920 --> 01:12:51.890 align:middle line:84%
And actually, because of
that, in this theorem,

01:12:51.890 --> 01:12:54.420 align:middle line:84%
if we were honest, it's a
little bit more complicated.

01:12:54.420 --> 01:12:59.000 align:middle line:90%


01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:03.540 align:middle line:84%
This would actually
be pi C of x,

01:13:03.540 --> 01:13:07.010 align:middle line:84%
where x is a subset
of A cross B and it's

01:13:07.010 --> 01:13:08.995 align:middle line:84%
like a delta to
the epsilon subset.

01:13:08.995 --> 01:13:12.080 align:middle line:90%


01:13:12.080 --> 01:13:15.600 align:middle line:84%
So we wouldn't have to
fill the whole product.

01:13:15.600 --> 01:13:16.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:16.100 --> 01:13:18.553 align:middle line:84%
So that's how we would
be careful about sharp

01:13:18.553 --> 01:13:20.470 align:middle line:84%
and how we would have
to be more careful here.

01:13:20.470 --> 01:13:23.840 align:middle line:90%


01:13:23.840 --> 01:13:25.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:25.340 --> 01:13:27.590 align:middle line:84%
Let me tell you
just the first idea

01:13:27.590 --> 01:13:31.750 align:middle line:90%
of the proof of this key lemma.

01:13:31.750 --> 01:13:36.890 align:middle line:90%


01:13:36.890 --> 01:13:41.550 align:middle line:90%
So we have step proof.

01:13:41.550 --> 01:13:44.380 align:middle line:90%


01:13:44.380 --> 01:13:50.230 align:middle line:84%
So we have A plus CB is only a
little bit bigger than A. That

01:13:50.230 --> 01:13:52.340 align:middle line:90%
reminds us of Plünnecke-Ruzsa.

01:13:52.340 --> 01:13:56.160 align:middle line:84%
So an appropriate version
of Plünnecke-Ruzsa.

01:13:56.160 --> 01:13:56.660 align:middle line:90%
Well, OK.

01:13:56.660 --> 01:13:57.890 align:middle line:90%
We have this big subset x.

01:13:57.890 --> 01:14:02.260 align:middle line:84%
We might want to get rid of that
by doing Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers.

01:14:02.260 --> 01:14:10.210 align:middle line:84%
So a Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers
would reduce to A prime plus CB

01:14:10.210 --> 01:14:13.480 align:middle line:90%
prime smaller than A prime.

01:14:13.480 --> 01:14:15.070 align:middle line:84%
We actually have
all of it instead

01:14:15.070 --> 01:14:17.350 align:middle line:90%
of just a big piece of it.

01:14:17.350 --> 01:14:23.420 align:middle line:84%
And then Plünnecke-Ruzsa
would give us--

01:14:23.420 --> 01:14:28.990 align:middle line:84%
so this would be
true for many C in C.

01:14:28.990 --> 01:14:34.460 align:middle line:84%
And that would give us A prime
plus C1, B prime plus C2,

01:14:34.460 --> 01:14:39.610 align:middle line:84%
B prime plus C3, B prime would
still be smaller than A prime.

01:14:39.610 --> 01:14:43.285 align:middle line:84%
You could get that
from Plünnecke-Ruzsa.

01:14:43.285 --> 01:14:45.580 align:middle line:84%
And so now we're not
done yet, but you

01:14:45.580 --> 01:14:48.663 align:middle line:84%
have the feeling
that we keep using

01:14:48.663 --> 01:14:50.330 align:middle line:84%
these tools from
additive combinatorics,

01:14:50.330 --> 01:14:54.160 align:middle line:84%
and we keep having stronger and
stronger sounding information

01:14:54.160 --> 01:14:59.170 align:middle line:84%
about A and B, more
and more suspicious.

01:14:59.170 --> 01:14:59.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:59.670 --> 01:15:04.150 align:middle line:84%
And it definitely takes some
skill and some good ideas

01:15:04.150 --> 01:15:05.503 align:middle line:90%
to finish from here.

01:15:05.503 --> 01:15:08.170 align:middle line:84%
But we're in a setting where the
tools of additive combinatorics

01:15:08.170 --> 01:15:11.175 align:middle line:84%
are quite powerful and they're
able to analyze what happens.

01:15:11.175 --> 01:15:18.070 align:middle line:90%


01:15:18.070 --> 01:15:19.250 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

01:15:19.250 --> 01:15:22.750 align:middle line:90%


01:15:22.750 --> 01:15:25.120 align:middle line:90%
Any final questions or comments?

01:15:25.120 --> 01:15:25.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:15:25.990 --> 01:15:28.982 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How did you reduce
to the projective case here?

01:15:28.982 --> 01:15:30.940 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: We reduce
to the projective case

01:15:30.940 --> 01:15:32.080 align:middle line:90%
at the beginning.

01:15:32.080 --> 01:15:35.420 align:middle line:90%


01:15:35.420 --> 01:15:39.080 align:middle line:84%
So after we had the
submultiplicative lemma,

01:15:39.080 --> 01:15:40.960 align:middle line:84%
we reduced to the
projective case

01:15:40.960 --> 01:15:46.990 align:middle line:84%
by saying that this ball
is in the projective case.

01:15:46.990 --> 01:15:51.280 align:middle line:84%
And so using that,
we were able to show

01:15:51.280 --> 01:15:55.148 align:middle line:84%
that it suffices to prove
it for the projective case.

01:15:55.148 --> 01:15:57.190 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But then how do
you chain that argument

01:15:57.190 --> 01:16:00.040 align:middle line:90%
in the projective case?

01:16:00.040 --> 01:16:01.233 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: What's that?

01:16:01.233 --> 01:16:02.650 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Like, I
don't understand

01:16:02.650 --> 01:16:07.840 align:middle line:84%
how you use that kind of
argument and the reduction

01:16:07.840 --> 01:16:10.450 align:middle line:90%
to projective at the same time.

01:16:10.450 --> 01:16:13.197 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Ah.

01:16:13.197 --> 01:16:15.280 align:middle line:84%
The question is about how
we put together reducing

01:16:15.280 --> 01:16:18.040 align:middle line:84%
to the projective case with all
the other things that we did.

01:16:18.040 --> 01:16:18.540 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:16:18.540 --> 01:16:22.120 align:middle line:90%


01:16:22.120 --> 01:16:22.730 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:22.730 --> 01:16:26.920 align:middle line:84%
So using this lemma,
we had an argument

01:16:26.920 --> 01:16:30.170 align:middle line:84%
that if you could prove a good
bound for the projective case,

01:16:30.170 --> 01:16:32.290 align:middle line:84%
then combining it
with this lemma

01:16:32.290 --> 01:16:34.590 align:middle line:84%
and noticing that
this is projective,

01:16:34.590 --> 01:16:37.220 align:middle line:84%
then we get a good bound
for the general case.

01:16:37.220 --> 01:16:38.810 align:middle line:84%
So now we just
imagine we're trying

01:16:38.810 --> 01:16:42.500 align:middle line:84%
to prove the theorem
in the projective case.

01:16:42.500 --> 01:16:46.070 align:middle line:84%
So we can assume that we're
in the projective case.

01:16:46.070 --> 01:16:49.330 align:middle line:84%
And then we start applying
the submultiplicative lemma.

01:16:49.330 --> 01:16:52.410 align:middle line:90%


01:16:52.410 --> 01:16:52.910 align:middle line:90%
Ah.

01:16:52.910 --> 01:16:54.790 align:middle line:84%
So you're wondering,
when we do this--

01:16:54.790 --> 01:16:58.430 align:middle line:90%


01:16:58.430 --> 01:16:59.310 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:16:59.310 --> 01:17:01.940 align:middle line:84%
So you can think
of in this picture

01:17:01.940 --> 01:17:08.000 align:middle line:84%
where, over here we have
not just some abstract thing

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:10.850 align:middle line:84%
but this would be the
R in the small ball

01:17:10.850 --> 01:17:13.130 align:middle line:90%
and the R for the fat tubes.

01:17:13.130 --> 01:17:18.380 align:middle line:84%
So we look at those, and if the
R is better than multiplying

01:17:18.380 --> 01:17:20.310 align:middle line:84%
the small balls
times the fat tubes,

01:17:20.310 --> 01:17:22.430 align:middle line:90%
then we keep breaking things up.

01:17:22.430 --> 01:17:25.380 align:middle line:84%
We can take the small balls and
break them into smaller balls.

01:17:25.380 --> 01:17:28.110 align:middle line:84%
And otherwise, if
they're comparable,

01:17:28.110 --> 01:17:32.230 align:middle line:84%
then we look at
what's happening.

01:17:32.230 --> 01:17:33.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:17:33.100 --> 01:17:34.310 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

01:17:34.310 --> 01:17:35.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:17:35.590 --> 01:17:38.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So I understand
what's going on.

01:17:38.720 --> 01:17:43.270 align:middle line:84%
Is this example supposed
to be similar to the case B

01:17:43.270 --> 01:17:45.700 align:middle line:84%
that we had at the
beginning where--

01:17:45.700 --> 01:17:49.900 align:middle line:84%
for instance, if we started
with tubes and points on a grid,

01:17:49.900 --> 01:17:53.180 align:middle line:84%
we kind of immediately fall
just into the situation.

01:17:53.180 --> 01:17:57.017 align:middle line:84%
And what we're doing is blowing
things up until we get there.

01:17:57.017 --> 01:17:57.850 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:17:57.850 --> 01:17:58.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:58.350 --> 01:18:02.590 align:middle line:84%
So the question is how these
pictures and these examples

01:18:02.590 --> 01:18:04.810 align:middle line:84%
relate to the three
examples that we

01:18:04.810 --> 01:18:07.060 align:middle line:90%
had in mind at the beginning.

01:18:07.060 --> 01:18:09.400 align:middle line:84%
So the three examples we
had in mind at the beginning

01:18:09.400 --> 01:18:11.840 align:middle line:84%
were there was a simple
one, the stars example.

01:18:11.840 --> 01:18:13.850 align:middle line:84%
There was the grid
that was interesting,

01:18:13.850 --> 01:18:16.570 align:middle line:84%
and there was the
random example.

01:18:16.570 --> 01:18:19.675 align:middle line:84%
And a funny thing is that
none of those is AD regular.

01:18:19.675 --> 01:18:22.540 align:middle line:90%


01:18:22.540 --> 01:18:26.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, the random
one, we could fidget

01:18:26.410 --> 01:18:29.110 align:middle line:84%
to make it AD regular
if we wanted to.

01:18:29.110 --> 01:18:32.050 align:middle line:84%
And the stars, we could make
it AD regular if we wanted to.

01:18:32.050 --> 01:18:35.910 align:middle line:84%
But the grid is actually
is really not AD regular.

01:18:35.910 --> 01:18:38.010 align:middle line:84%
And so that is a
little bit funny

01:18:38.010 --> 01:18:41.700 align:middle line:84%
that in the most important
example it's not in this case,

01:18:41.700 --> 01:18:46.890 align:middle line:84%
even though this case is very
important in the final proof.

01:18:46.890 --> 01:18:49.745 align:middle line:84%
So you can't really
start with the grid.

01:18:49.745 --> 01:18:55.120 align:middle line:90%


01:18:55.120 --> 01:18:56.970 align:middle line:84%
At least until
recently, it was not

01:18:56.970 --> 01:19:03.060 align:middle line:84%
known what is the actual worst
behavior in the AD regular case.

01:19:03.060 --> 01:19:09.420 align:middle line:84%
So it may be that RAD
is much smaller than R,

01:19:09.420 --> 01:19:12.360 align:middle line:84%
but the argument so
far doesn't prove that.

01:19:12.360 --> 01:19:14.190 align:middle line:84%
And it's a little
bit funny because it

01:19:14.190 --> 01:19:15.780 align:middle line:84%
means there's not
an example that you

01:19:15.780 --> 01:19:20.910 align:middle line:84%
can keep in mind when you go
through the AD regular case.

01:19:20.910 --> 01:19:22.440 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:19:22.440 --> 01:19:25.410 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What goes wrong
with trying to construct an AD

01:19:25.410 --> 01:19:27.460 align:middle line:84%
regular grid where you
just kind of have a grid,

01:19:27.460 --> 01:19:31.117 align:middle line:84%
and each point has some
nested subgrids within it?

01:19:31.117 --> 01:19:31.950 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:19:31.950 --> 01:19:33.550 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, could
you make an AD-- yeah,

01:19:33.550 --> 01:19:34.383 align:middle line:90%
I guess that's true.

01:19:34.383 --> 01:19:36.180 align:middle line:84%
You could make a
roughly somewhat

01:19:36.180 --> 01:19:39.580 align:middle line:84%
AD regular grid by
taking a grid of balls,

01:19:39.580 --> 01:19:42.210 align:middle line:84%
and then in each one of those
balls, you put a grid of balls

01:19:42.210 --> 01:19:43.295 align:middle line:90%
and you repeat like this.

01:19:43.295 --> 01:19:47.670 align:middle line:90%


01:19:47.670 --> 01:19:51.960 align:middle line:84%
Since the grid itself is not
AD regular, this is only--

01:19:51.960 --> 01:19:57.700 align:middle line:84%
it's only AD regular with
the big C. Could you do that?

01:19:57.700 --> 01:19:59.540 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I guess you could do that.

01:19:59.540 --> 01:20:04.830 align:middle line:90%


01:20:04.830 --> 01:20:05.390 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:20:05.390 --> 01:20:05.890 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:20:05.890 --> 01:20:07.510 align:middle line:90%
So you could do that.

01:20:07.510 --> 01:20:10.350 align:middle line:84%
And then what would happen
here, the A, B, and C

01:20:10.350 --> 01:20:13.440 align:middle line:84%
would be like sets of
integers except they would

01:20:13.440 --> 01:20:15.160 align:middle line:90%
have this AD regular structure.

01:20:15.160 --> 01:20:18.270 align:middle line:84%
So A would be, take an
arithmetic progression

01:20:18.270 --> 01:20:21.060 align:middle line:84%
of intervals, and
in each one of them,

01:20:21.060 --> 01:20:24.070 align:middle line:84%
put an arithmetic progression
of small intervals and so on.

01:20:24.070 --> 01:20:25.920 align:middle line:84%
That's what A and B
and C would look like.

01:20:25.920 --> 01:20:27.378 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Like a
Cantor set looked?

01:20:27.378 --> 01:20:27.450 align:middle line:90%


01:20:27.450 --> 01:20:27.970 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:20:27.970 --> 01:20:28.762 align:middle line:90%
It's kind of like--

01:20:28.762 --> 01:20:31.620 align:middle line:84%
it's like a Cantor
set, but in order

01:20:31.620 --> 01:20:34.455 align:middle line:84%
to make the numbers
come out well,

01:20:34.455 --> 01:20:37.140 align:middle line:84%
you need to have a lot of
intervals in an arithmetic

01:20:37.140 --> 01:20:39.600 align:middle line:90%
progression in each step.

01:20:39.600 --> 01:20:43.320 align:middle line:84%
Here, I'll draw it, and then
I'm over, so I'm going to stop.

01:20:43.320 --> 01:20:48.210 align:middle line:90%
So the example is a big line.

01:20:48.210 --> 01:20:50.550 align:middle line:84%
You make an
arithmetic progression

01:20:50.550 --> 01:20:52.396 align:middle line:90%
with a lot of intervals.

01:20:52.396 --> 01:20:58.500 align:middle line:90%


01:20:58.500 --> 01:20:59.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:20:59.220 --> 01:21:01.560 align:middle line:84%
Then you look inside of
each one of these intervals

01:21:01.560 --> 01:21:03.960 align:middle line:90%
